<HEADLINE> President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Neither NATO troops nor nuclear
weapons will be deployed in Poland upon its admission to the
alliance, Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski told a Russian
newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
Poland, along with Hungary and the Czech Republic, will
officially join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization Friday at a
ceremony in the U.S. town of Independence, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski told the Izvestia newspaper that Poland will
continue its reduction of troops from 240,000 to 180,000 and the
cut in the duration of mandatory military service to one year.
</P>
<P>
On Poland's ties with Russia, Kwasniewski said "a lot has been
lost from the rich potential previously amassed" but that the
situation can be rectified, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski noted with satisfaction the revival of bilateral
dialogue, adding that Warsaw is looking forward to Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov's upcoming visit to Poland.
</P>
<P>
He said the invitation to Russian President Boris Yeltsin to
make an official visit to Warsaw remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewsky said he hopes Yeltsin's visit will materialize and
that it "would become a turning point at this stage of our history
and give a new impetus to the development of diverse ties."
</P>
</TEXT>
