<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Rejects Foreign Military Presence in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has firmly and resolutely rejected any possibility of a
multinational military or police operation in Kosovo, Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov, who met with Milosevic earlier Friday, told reporters
in Belgrade the Yugoslav authorities "are guided by the belief
that they can, jointly with an OSCE observation mission in Kosovo,
ensure the implementation of the agreements which are expected to
be reached in Paris," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov quoted Milosevic as saying that "the Yugoslav delegation
will arrive in Paris on March 15 to continue the talks with the
Kosovo Albanians."
</P>
<P>
"In Belgrade's opinion, the political document drafted on the
basis of the talks in Rambouillet (France) will lay a solid
foundation for reaching political agreements on granting broad
autonomy to Kosovo with the strict observance of the sovereignty
and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that after the talks in Rambouillet,
a political document along with two supplements on military and
police implementation of the future agreements were offered to the
negotiating parties by the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
Russia is a member of the six-nation Contact Group on former
Yugoslavia, which also includes Britain, France, Germany, Italy
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the supplements "were proposed by individual
members of the Contact Group" but Moscow believes a political
document should be signed first, and that "the parameters of its
implementation should be discussed afterwards."
</P>
<P>
"All members of the Contact Group understand that neither a
military nor a police operation can be carried out in Kosovo
without Belgrade's consent," Ivanov added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
