<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Recommended to Head German Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gerhard Glogowski, SPD premier of Lower Saxony, told reporters
the party executive had agreed to back Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Oscar Lafontaine on Thursday surprisingly quit his post as
finance minister and chairman of the party.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine's resignation, following a bitter cabinet row, ended
months of power struggle with the federal chancellor, who is
expected to consolidate his standing by seeking the leadership
over the party.
</P>
<P>
However, given the strong support for Lafontaine in the party,
there is a danger that a less emphatic vote for Schroeder could
further damage his power base, critics indicated.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to limit damage to the five-month-old government, SPD
leaders stressed the center-left alliance with the Greens remained
stable despite Lafontaine's resignation.
</P>
<P>
"We want this coalition to continue working through the end of
the legislature period," said SPD parliamentary leader, Peter
Struck.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder was elected for a four-year term last September in a
coalition with the Greens. His government was sworn a month later.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Germany's Allensbach polling institute predicted
tough times ahead for Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of voters no longer believed Schroeder would
succeed in cutting Germany's near post-war record unemployment
which rose to 11.6 percent in February, said Allensbach Director,
Renate Koecher.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent believe the government will raise taxes
rather than cut taxes as Schroeder has promised, said Koecher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
