<HEADLINE> Romania, Bulgaria, Turkey Hail NATO's Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Presidents of Romania,
Bulgaria and Turkey on Friday sent a congratulatory telegram to
their counterparts in the Czech Republic, Poland and Hungary on
their countries' formal entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Romania's President Emil Constantinescu, Bulgaria's President
Petar Stoianov and Turkey's President Suleyman Demirel, who just
ended a two-day trilateral summit meeting in Romanian mountain
resort Sinaia, agreed that the accession of the three countries to
NATO will enhances regional security.
</P>
<P>
The three heads of state signed on Friday, at the end of the
trilateral summit, a joint statement on NATO's expansion. The
statement expresses their firm confidence that further enlargement
of the Alliance, to South-Eastern Europe in particular, would
represent a key contribution to the stability of the region as
well as of the whole continent.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the forthcoming NATO Summit in Washington as an
important event, which will outline prospects for the Alliance
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The Presidents expected the NATO summit to enhance the momentum
of the enlargement process by firmly attesting that countries
which have significantly contributed to NATO's values and
objectives and advanced in their efforts to meet accession
criteria, like Romania and Bulgaria, are regarded as future Allies.
</P>
<P>
They also expected the Summit to define a clear membership
perspective for these two states, accompanied by a substantial
accession strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
