<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Union Criticizes Banana Dispute by Big Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Confederation of Labor
(WCL) on Friday criticized the United States and European Union (
EU) for their dispute over bananas, saying that both sides did not
mention working conditions on the banana plantations in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The WCL, along with its member union, the World Federation of
Agriculture and Food Workers (WFAFW) said in a statement that "the
notorious banana dispute has taken a technical shape, veiling what
is really at stake."
</P>
<P>
"Whereas the two blocs, Europe and the United States, lash out
at each other with commercial standards, not a word is said about
the working conditions on the plantations, where the workers sweat
out the measures to lower the production cost," they said.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels based WCL has its member unions in 130 developing
countries in the world. Andre Linard, the organization's press
staff, said the WCL represents over 26 million workers mainly in
South American, African and Asia Pacific regions, as well as a
small number of workers in North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The WCL and WFAFW pointed out that in developing countries'
banana plantations, low wages, delayed payment, diseases resulting
from the use of pesticides, and dismissal of workers who join a
trade union are the normal practice.
</P>
<P>
The two unions also said the banana dispute is not a
geographical issue in its nature. "It opposes the multinational
corporations, which want to control the whole market, to the small
producers and the workers. Those corporations make considerable
profits which they use to finance election campaigns so as to have
their private interests protected by the public authorities," said
the WCL and WFAFW.
</P>
<P>
The United States on March 3 announced unilaterally that it
would impose 520 million US dollars in import duties on European
products to compensate for losses allegedly suffered by American
companies in the Latin American banana market. The US believes the
EU has failed to reform its import regime enough to remove any
discrimination against imports by US-run corporations, and insists
that the regime is still in favor of some former European colonies
in African, Caribbean and Pacific regions.
</P>
<P>
EU officials argue that Caribbean farmers are small scale and
cannot grow their crops as cheaply as the large estates of Latin
America. Bananas are the staple of these islands' economies,
providing as much as 60 percent of their export earnings, so any
free trade regime would condemn them to absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the effect of losing the preferential treatment from
the EU would be devastating for the poor Caribbean countries, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The WCL and WFAFW noted that the United States has declared
that it is a "matter of principle:" respect for the regulations of
the World Trade Organization. Yet, both unions wonder if
principles wreck the economies of a number of small countries and
have serious human consequences, wouldn't it be better to
challenge the legitimacy of those principles -- the "market at any
cost?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
