<HEADLINE> Romania, Bulgaria, Turkey Urges Kosovo Parties to Make Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Romania, Bulgaria and Turkey
appealed to the Kosovo conflict parties on Friday to reach a peace
agreement in the new round of talks scheduled to begin in France
on March 15.
</P>
<P>
Romania's President Emil Constantinescu, Bulgaria's President
Petar Stoianov and Turkey's President Suleyman Demirel made the
appeal at the end of a two-day summit in Sinaia, a mountain resort
some 150 kilometers north of Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The presidents expressed deep concern about the current
situation in Kosovo, saying that the Kosovo crisis not only
threatened regional peace and stability but also may bring about
adverse results to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that Kosovo's substantial autonomy must respect
Yugoslavia's territorial integrity and the legitimate rights and
freedoms of various ethnic groups in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The presidents reiterated their support of all international
efforts made to peacefully solve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The summit is the third of a series that opened in Varna of
Bulgaria, the second was held in Antalya, Turkey, after the
Romania-Bulgaria-Turkey trilateral was inaugurated in September
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
