<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CICP Proposes New Plans To Fight Rise in Int'l Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Vienna-based Center
of International Crime Prevention (CICP) had announced the launch
of three new global programs aimed at curbing the growth of
illegal international activities, a U.N. release said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new strategies are against corruption, trafficking in human
beings and organized criminal groups.
</P>
<P>
The release also said the CICP and the U.N. Interregional Crime
and Justice Research Institute have agreed to conduct a joint
worldwide study on corruption as part of a three-year global
program against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Other components of the project include the establishment of an
international database containing updated information on the
study's results, best anti-corruption practices and international
instruments against corruption; and technical cooperation projects
to assist countries in building or strengthening their ability to
prevent, detect and fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
The two agencies will also collaborate on the global program
against trafficking in human beings, which will focus on the
growing involvement of organized criminal groups with smuggling
and trafficking human beings.
</P>
<P>
The global studies on organized crime will assess organized
criminal groups worldwide and give countries reliable information
and analysis on emerging transnational criminal organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
