<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vinegar Could Be Used for Screening Cervical Cancer: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Vinegar has proved to be useful as
a cheap and effective screening test for cervical cancer,
scientists said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that vinegar, or acetic acid, could be used
where the standard Pap smear is unavailable or too expensive and
could improve the chances of preventing cervical cancer in the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
The researchers, from Johns Hopkins University, the United
States, and the University of Zimbabwe, evaluated the vinegar
screening test in a study of 10,000 women at 15 clinics in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Their results, published in the medical journal The Lancet,
concluded that the test was safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
The new test involves a visual inspection of the cervix as
opposed to sending a sample to a laboratory. The doctors simply
wash the cervix with dilute acetic acid and then inspect it by
eye.
</P>
<P>
The women studied were screened using both the acetic acid test
and the traditional method. The researchers found that both
techniques had a similar detection rate.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said it has proved that the new method "can
identify most true cases of cervical pre-cancer and cancer."
</P>
<P>
Cervical cancer is one of the most common cancers affecting
women, killing 200,000 each year, and is the leading cause of
cancer deaths in parts of Africa, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists said that the earlier the cancer is
detected, the better the chances of defeating it. If it is caught
before it spreads beyond the cervix, 95 percent of cases are
believed to be curable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
