<HEADLINE> S-300 Missiles to Be Deployed on Crete in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Russian-made S-300
anti-aircraft missiles, ordered by Cyprus, will be transferred to
Greece's Crete island in mid-1999, the Cyprus News Agency (CNA)
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
With all legal and technical matters of the deal now settled,
what remains to be completed is Greece's preparatory works for the
deployment, CNA said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian media reported that by the end of July 1999,
Moscow will be ready to deploy six batteries of TOR M1 short-range
missiles in Greece, and that by the end of 2000, Athens will
receive another 15 such missile batteries.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the S-300 missile system in January 1997 in a
bid to bolster its air defense capability. The move was cursed by
Turkey, which termed it a threat to security and vowed to take
pre-emptive measures should the missiles be deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The United States and some other Western countries also opposed
the deal and pressured Cyprus to cancel its implementation to
prevent an escalation of tension between Cyprus and Greece on the
one side, and Turkey and Turkish Cypriots on the other.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides announced on December 29,
1998 that the missiles will be deployed not in Cyprus, but in
Greece's Crete island, about 500 kilometers in the west, instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
