<HEADLINE> UK Warns Parliament to Prepare for Strikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- British government ministers
Friday warned the parliament that British armed forces could soon
take part in strikes against Yugoslavia if talks next week fail to
secure peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a joint letter written to all members of parliament, Junior
Foreign Minister Tony Lloyd and Junior Defense Minister Doug
Henderson said that MPs should prepare for the talks to fail.
</P>
<P>
"Belgrade may choose to reject the agreement and/or launch a
major offensive, leading to an overwhelming human catastrophe,"
the two ministers said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Britain was prepared to take necessary action to avert that
catastrophe, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"In this crucial period, (Yugoslav) President (Slobodan)
Milosovic and his commanders must understand that NATO will not
stand by in the face of oppression and atrocities in Kosovo," said
the letter.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook is scheduled to travel to
Paris Monday to co-chair a second round of talks between
representatives of Yugoslavia and ethnic Albanians living in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the two sides held 17 days of negotiations in
France. The talks failed as both of the rivalry parties refused to
sign the treaty initiated by the Contact Group, which promised a
substantial autonomy to the Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
There has been no sign that the two parties would reach an
agreement in the next round of talks. Albanians told United States
mediator Bob Dole last week that they would sign the treaty but
later withdraw from the stand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
