<HEADLINE> U.N. Relief Staff to Return to Afghanistan in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations had
decided to send back a limited number of international relief
staff to Afghanistan in the following weeks, U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations pulled all of its international staff out of
the country after three of them were murdered last July and
August.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to return has been taken following evidence and
progress in the investigation of the three murders and concerted
efforts by the Taleban to comply with a security agreement it
signed with the United Nations last October," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"Other determining factors include recent assessments of the
security conditions in the country and a vision of common U.N.
strategy for Afghanistan for the coming months," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations would continue to monitor closely the
situation in Afghanistan as a basis for its continued presence in
the country, Eckhard added. 
