<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia Must Reach Agreement With IMF on Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
said here Friday that Russia must reach an agreement with the
International Monetary Fund on its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
"We can't progress in relations with the World Bank until we
reach agreement with the IMF, and most critical, we can't complete
a restructuring deal with the London and Paris clubs," Primakov
told an expanded session of the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
"Untied loans have been blocked completely, and tied loans have
been complicated," Interfax quoted Primakov as saying.
</P>
<P>
An IMF delegation led by Gegard Belanger, deputy director of
the Second European Department, is here negotiating with the
Russian government.
</P>
<P>
"We need an agreement with the IMF, but this doesn't mean that
this will be the main support in the development of the domestic
economy," Primakov said. "This isn't so. But an agreement is
important anyway."
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, the
country's domestic and foreign debt had topped 100 billion U.S.
dollars by August, with debt on Treasury bills and federal loan
bonds over 80 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On August 17 last year, the former government of Sergei
Kiriyenko devalued the ruble and declared a 90-day moratorium on
some foreign debts, an effective default seen by many economists.
</P>
<P>
The ruble has since tumbled to 23 to the U.S. dollar from the
pre-crisis exchange rate of 6.3 rubles to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Zadornov attributed the August crisis to excessive borrowing in
foreign and domestic markets to finance budget spending, noting
that debts of regional budgets were 40-50 percent of annual
revenue.
</P>
<P>
Short-term debt of commercial banks and companies had grown to
30 billion to 40 billion dollars by July.
</P>
<P>
"An illusion of a balance and economic stability was formed
while we were living in debt, but a change in external conditions
put colossal pressure on the entire unstable structure," Zadornov
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
