<HEADLINE> Rwandan PM Accused of Involvement in Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Prime Minister Pierre Celestin
Rwigema has been charged by one member of parliament from his own
party, the Republican Democratic Party (MDR), of having been involved in
the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister who is persecuting us is accused of having been
involved in the genocide, and of being a Hutu extremist," Jacques
Maniraguha said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to Tuesday's decision of the forum of eight political
parties forming the current transitional government and parliament to expel
four MPs from the MDR party from parliament, reported the Rwandan
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The forum, chaired by the Secretary General of the Rwandese Patriotic
Front (RPF), Charles Muligande, had ordered Maniraguha, and three other MPs
from MDR, Jean Baptiste Sebarame, Eustache Nkerinka, and Jean Leonard
Bizimana to resign from their seats within 15 days, or else they would be
sacked from their party.
</P>
<P>
The four are accused of a number of charges including absenteeism during
parliamentary sessions, and acts relating to troubling the security of the
state in backing the Hutu Interahamwe militia.
</P>
<P>
But the four declared Friday that this decision is unconstitutional, and
said they will not resign. They charged the prime minister of being the
instigator of their expulsion in smearing their reputation, because they
had opposed his taking over of the chairmanship of the party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
