<HEADLINE> Annan Expresses Sadness Over Death of Violinist Menuhin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday expressed his great sadness over the death of
Britain's violinist Yehudi Menuhin.
</P>
<P>
Sir Yehudi Menuhin, one of the world's most famous violinists
and music teachers, died in Berlin Friday at the age of 82.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said,
"Yehudi Menuhin was not only a great musician whose art brought
joy to millions of people all over the world. He was also a
brilliant teacher and a citizen of the world in the fullest sense
-- one whose vision and culture gave him a deep empathy with
fellow human beings of every creed and color, and who constantly
sought to place his fame and wisdom at the service of humanity."
</P>
<P>
"I was privileged to meet him many times and was always
impressed by the sweetness of his nature and the breadth of his
concerns," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"As a member of a people which more than any other has been the
victim of this century's barbarism, he redeemed the century by
rising above all resentment and showing what human beings at their
best are capable of," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The world is a sadder place without him, but his music, and
his example, will endure," Annan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
