<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Well Still Burning In India's Western Offshore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The gas well in India's
Western offshore which caught fire Friday is still burning, with
the area virtually covered by water umbrella to prevent the fire
from spreading and damaging the rig and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
Oil and Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC), owner of the well, was
awaiting the arrival on Sunday of two experts from the United
States to assess the burning well and chalk out an action plan to
put out the fire, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Saturday
from Mumbai, about 1,400 kilometers southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
An uncontrolled flow of gas, which began at 09:30 local time on
Thursday from a well numbering "B-121-D," started spewing fire
from 12:20 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
The flow of gas was connected to other five platforms
comprising wells nearby, according to an ONGC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
PTI said that multi-purpose support vehicles were spraying
water at a rate of 20,000 cubic meters per hour to ensure that the
rig and other equipment remain cool and damage prevented.
</P>
<P>
ONGC is suffering a loss of around 1.6 million cubic meters of
gas a day, or 3 percent of the total gas production in the Western
offshore.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to say when the fire would be brought under
control," PTI quoted an ONGC director as saying.
</P>
<P>
A regional contingency plan has been activated. The Regional
Contingency Committee comprises, among others, ONGC, navy, coast
guard, air force, state government authorities and other companies
and organizations involving in marine activity.
</P>
<P>
The B-121 platform, which produces 2 million cubic meters of
gas per day, was reportedly shut down for maintenance work two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
There are 126 well platforms in the Western offshore, some 160
kilometers off Mumbai, of which only nine are purely gas platforms
and the rests are oil-cum-gas platforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
