<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Nations Staff to Return to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations announced
here Saturday that U.N. staff would begin a gradual process of
return to their posts inside Afghanistan beginning on March 16.
</P>
<P>
Following a decision of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, a
limited number of international staff will be allowed to resume
their humanitarian work inside the country, said a press release
issued Saturday by the Office for Coordination of Humanitarian
Assistance to Afghanistan (UNOCHA).
</P>
<P>
On August 22, 1998, 40 international U.N. staff were evacuated
from all locations in Afghanistan following a series of incidents
targeting U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
Two Afghan staff members from the World Food Program (WFP) and
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees were abducted
and murdered in Jalalabad last July.
</P>
<P>
In August, following U.S. bombing raids in Khost, Afghanistan,
UNOCHA and WFP offices in Jalalabad were attacked by a mob, and
one day later U.N. military observer Lt. Colonel Carmine Calo was
murdered in the streets of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The release said that U.N. programs managed locally by national
staff working in Afghanistan have continued under the supervision
of international staff evacuated to Islamabad, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator for Afghanistan Erik de Mul has
expressed his appreciation for the dedication shown by U.N. Afghan
staff during this challenging period, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the Afghan Taliban militia signed a
security protocol on October 24, 1998 and have met to discuss
security issues in Kandahar, Kabul of Afghanistan and Islamabad.
Last month, a technical observation mission, headed by a
specialist in judicial processes and investigations, traveled to
Kabul to assess the status of the investigations in three
murdering cases.
</P>
<P>
The mission concluded that the Taliban had made a satisfactory
and concerted effort to resolve these cases, said the release.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of this investigation, the release said, the
United Nations next sent security assessment missions to Kabul,
Herat, Kandahar and Jalalabad, which determined that the
environment in these areas was conducive for the return of what
will initially be limited number of international staff.
</P>
<P>
International staff from the UNOCHA, WFP, the United Nations
Children's Fund and the World Health Organization will be
stationed in Kabul to begin with, the release said.
</P>
<P>
In the week from March 22, international staff from various
agencies will resume work in Kandahar. If the security environment
remains stable, this will be followed by the return of staff to
Herat and Jalalabad.
</P>
<P>
Following the return of international staff to Kabul, the
United Nations will resume negotiations with the Taliban on issues
of education and health, according to the release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
