<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Growth of Non-Public Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Deputies attending the on-going
Second Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC),
China's top lawmaking body, have pinned high hopes on the
confirmation of the status of the private economic sector in a
constitutional amendment proposed by the NPC Standing Committee,
</P>
<P>
They called it a true reform to boost the fledgling sector.
</P>
<P>
"The amendment, if passed, will give us a big relief," said
Liang Wengen, a private business boss from Hunan Province, "
legally speaking, I feel a real equality." The private businesses
are facing a good opportunity of development and "we should be
bolder to go ahead," he noted.
</P>
<P>
All private enterprises in the country were changed into firms
of joint state-private ownership in the 1950s, and private
enterprises emerged again in the late 1970s when the government
began its reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report by the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, the number of private firms has grown from 90,000 about
a decade ago to the present more than one million. Official
statistics show that by the end of last year, China had more than
32 million workers employed by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the annual added value of the non-public industrial
enterprises accounts for 50 percent of the country's total annual
industrial added value.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Fifteenth National Congress of the ruling
Communist Party of China (CPC) said explicitly in its report that
the non-public sector is an important component of the country's
socialist market economy and the sector should be further
encouraged. The proposed constitutional amendment gives expression
to this principle.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, local governments at different levels have
issued or will publish new policies to boost the private sector.
Private businesses have been encouraged to participate in the
restructuring of the public sector through various means such as
share-holding, purchase, merger and leasing.
</P>
<P>
Lu Guanqiu, a well-known township-based industrialist who has
exported his products to many foreign countries, said that the
private businesses' participation in the reform of state
enterprises will inject new vitality into the state firms and will
also lead to a rapid expansion of the private sector. He believed
it will help adjust the pattern of industries and the mix of
products of the country.
</P>
<P>
To further encourage the private sector this year, the central
government granted earlier this year 61 private companies the
permission to export or import goods, which had been a franchise
only enjoyed by some state-owned factories.
</P>
<P>
In a recent speech, Governor of the People's Bank of China Dai
Xianglong announced that local banks will no longer issues loans
to companies according to their types of ownership, but will do
only according to their performance.
</P>
<P>
Some NPC deputies said that with the support of state policies
and credits, the non-public sector will greatly increase their
competitiveness and expand their scope of businesses. Large
private enterprise groups will come into being and will play an
important role in the country's economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
