<HEADLINE> China Must Practice Strict Land Resource Management, Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today stressed that China, a developing country with the world's
largest population, must apply strict land resource management
practices.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a work conference on population control and
resources and environmental protection attended by high-ranking
Party and government officials, Jiang said that all regions must
prevent any further shrinkage in cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
"No department or unit should be allowed to illegally occupy
land managed by farmers according to land contracts," said Jiang,
who also serves as general secretary of the Communist Party of
China Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said China's land and natural resources must be strictly
protected and managed, with the development and protection of
resources carried out simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said priority must be placed to practicing thrift when
developing resources, and noted that efficiency must be upgraded
in order to ensure the intensive rather than extensive use of
resources.
</P>
<P>
He said a new resource management system should be established
to respond to requirements for developing the socialist market
economy. The centralized system will not only be highly efficient
and authoritative, but also be conducive to strengthening planning,
managing, protecting and ensuring the rational utilization of
resources nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China now faces an extremely acute shortage of water
and must practice conservation, prevent pollution and strengthen
management to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Saving water must be a long-term measure applicable to all
trades and people from all walks of life, said Jiang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
