<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unified Contract Law Good for Orderly Development of China's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Li Li, a law expert from Guangzhou University, said the
old contract laws were formulated in the years when the concept of
market economy was not established, so they bear the mark of the
planned economy, with more stresses on administrative power. There
are too many restrictions on the contract freedom of the parties
involved in the contract, and the main party in the concept of the
economic contract is social organization in those contract laws,
which do not cover explicitly the multiple contract parties, that
is, the existing state-owned enterprises and non-public businesses.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that some four billion contracts are
signed a year in China. In 1997, there were 1.5 million cases of
economic disputes in the country, mostly involving economic
contracts, and among the three million civil cases handled in the
same year by the courts at all levels, 1.4 million cases were
contract disputes.
</P>
<P>
Lu Weizhong, an NPC deputy and vice-chairman of the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Regional Federation of Industry and Commerce,
said that the draft unified contract law has a clearer definition
about the responsibilities of the party who violates the contract
compared with the existing three contract laws.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhongqi, general manager of the Yangtze River Group
Corporation, said that it is a remarkable feature of the draft
unified contract law which absorbs new experience from developed
countries and complies to the international practice, and
therefore, it will serve to further promote the country's opening
up drive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unified Contract Law Good for Orderly Development of China's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The existing three contract laws
have many pitfalls and loopholes and Chinese companies often get
trapped when signing or executing contracts," an NPC deputy from
central China's Hubei province said in an interview with Xinhua
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li Guojin, an entrepreneur from Wuhan, capital of central China'
s Hubei Province, is one of the some 2,800 deputies to the ongoing
session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's
highest lawmaking body.
</P>
<P>
Li Guojin said that he had come up with many troubles or even
disputes in his business, mostly involving contracts, he said.
</P>
<P>
While deliberating a draft unified contract law submitted to
the current NPC session to replace the existing three contract
laws, Li Guojin said that the unified contract law, the first of
its kind in China if adopted, is the urgent need of the developing
market economy of the country and an effective guarantee for the
orderly development of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
The three existing contract laws are the Law of Economic
Contracts, Law for Sino-Foreign Economic Contracts and Law of
Technical Contracts. They were formulated in the early 1980s or
the mid-1980s and are not suited to the need of the social life
and economic development with the deepening of the reforms and
opening up drive, according to the NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
The new unified contract law draft is conducive to enlivening
commodities circulation, expanding domestic demand and promoting
the sustainable and healthy development of the market-driven
economy, according to some law experts who are NPC deputies.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Chengsi, Member of the NPC Law Committee and a researcher
of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, said the existing three
contract laws no longer meet the demand of the fast developing
market-driven economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
