<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clashes Renewed in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The relative stability around
the main market of Karan District, north Mogadishu, was shattered
Friday by heavy clashes between militiamen loyal to Muse Sudi
Yalahow and others organized by the business community in the
market.
</P>
<P>
At least two people were killed and five others wounded when
about five battle wagons and dozens of heavily armed militiamen
exchanged fire in the security men of the market.
</P>
<P>
According to an eyewitness in the market, the victims who were
mainly civilians caught in the cross fire.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the clashes are not officiated. However, the
businessmen in the market have accused Muse Sudi Yalahow of asking
for a forceful taxation from every businessman in the market.
</P>
<P>
Muse Sudi Yalahow, who is among the leaders opposing to
Mogadishu's administration announced by Ali Mahdi and Hussein
Aidid, believes that he has the right to collect tax after freeing
the area from the bandits who made the road to Karan market almost
impassable. But the businessmen worried that they would not be
recognized as neutral businessmen once they give money to any of
the opposing politicians of the capital.
</P>
<P>
There has been no official ceasefire tentative between the two
sides Saturday as the opposing militiamen still remain in
defensive positions around the market.
</P>
<P>
Early in the week, militiamen loyal to Muse Sudi Yalahow had
cracked down bandits who extorted money from the commercial
traffic in illegal roadblocks not very far from this same market
area of Karan District.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 armed gangs have been rounded up from various
roadblocks between Karan and El-Adde, about 15 km north of
Mogadishu, and are waiting for Islamic trials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
