<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Roundup Roundup: Poland, Hungary, Czech Republic Join NATO With Mixed Feeling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic formally joined the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (
NATO) on Friday in a ceremony in Missouri, the United States. This
is a step of significance in NATO's enlargement that will have a
strong impact on the political and security pattern of Europe in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three countries hailed their countries' NATO
membership, saying the move accomplished their long-time dream of
"returning to Europe" and would strengthen peace and security in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized their countries' NATO membership was not
directed at any third party and hoped it would not affect
negatively the relations between the three and Russia either.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have made constant efforts for joining the
military alliance since the Warsaw Pact dismembered in 1991.
</P>
<P>
They have reformed their political systems and economic and
military structures to move closer to the Western countries.
Internationally, they have coordinated their policies with them.
</P>
<P>
Their efforts coincided with the strategic aim of the United
States which seeks to weaken Russia so as to control Europe.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the United States and other Western countries,
the three countries started their NATO membership talks in 1997
and completed the legal procedures on the matter in February when
their parliaments ratified the related documents.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, disputes over whether to join the NATO have never
stopped in these three countries, with a recent poll showing a big
number of people still opposing the NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
These people argued that the NATO membership could jeopardize
their countries' decision-making power in the political and
diplomatic issues, threat peace and security of Europe and even
hurt the national interests of their countries.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the three countries would face many
Gordian knots after joining NATO.
</P>
<P>
First, with limited economic power, it would be very hard for
them to bear their share of expensive defense obligations of NATO.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the NATO enlargement would cost about 35
billion U.S. dollars. The United States has promised only 2
billion dollars and the other NATO members have agreed to give 16
billion dollars. Naturally, the rest will have to be covered by
the new members themselves.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the three countries would find it difficult to
coordinate their relations with both Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
With contradictions between Europe and the United States
increasing day by day, the three countries will have to measure
their steps so as to offend neither of them, though both
geographically and historically they feel closer to West Europe.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, they would find it difficult to handle their relations
with Russia and their non-NATO neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Russia always strongly opposes the NATO's eastern expansion. On
Thursday, in a statement, the Russian foreign ministry made it
clear that the NATO expansion would not be constructive to trust
and stability in the international relations, rather it would only
create new rifts in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the three countries need to make painstaking efforts
to manage well their traditional relations with Russia and the non-
NATO countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
Joining the NATO is just the beginning of something new for the
three countries. Just as Polish president Aleksander Kwasniewski
said soon after the Missouri ceremony that more efforts are needed
now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Currency Assets Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- India's foreign currency assets
increased by 86 million U.S. dollars to 27.865 billion dollars
during the week ending March 5 this year, the Press Trust of India
(PTI) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Gold reserves went up by 2 million dollars to 2.971 billion
dollars, thus pushing the total foreign exchange reserves up by 88
million dollars to 30.844 billion dollars, according to the weekly
Statistical Supplement published by the Reserve Bank of India in
Mumbai.
</P>
<P>
Bank credit to the commercial sector increased by 20.74 billion
rupees (490 million dollars) during the fortnight ending February
26, PTI reported from Mumbai.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of March 1998, banks' non-food credit has gone up
by 231.17 billion rupees (some 5.5 billion dollars), the
supplement showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
