<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Builds Ecological Province in Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost province of
Hainan plans to build itself into the nation's first ecological
province, said a Hainan leader, Du Qinglin, who is here attending
the ongoing Second Session of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC), China's top lawmaking body.
</P>
<P>
"Hainan plans to build this largest special economic zone in
China into a tropical ecological island within ten to 15 years,
featuring special ecological scenes, environment of first-rate
quality, burgeoning ecological agriculture and better-protected
ecological sources." Du Qinglin said.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan Island, the second largest of the country next to
Taiwan, covers an area of 34,000 square kilometers, ranking one of
the best in China in environment quality with its rich tropical
natural resources including more than 4,000 species of tropical
plants.
</P>
<P>
The plan for the next five years spells out as to maintain the
first-rate environment quality, achieve the highest forest
coverage rate in the nation, curb deforestation, keep industrial
pollution under control, protect natural resources, expand
ecological industries, and improve the life quality of the local
residents, according to the deputy.
</P>
<P>
"Hainan has focused on sustainable economic development from
the very beginning, paying equal attention to economic development
and environment protection," Du said, adding "Hainan's pillar
industries of tropical agriculture, tourism and high and new
technologies also tally with its goal of building an ecological
province."
</P>
<P>
Hainan will focus its ecological agriculture on developing and
producing wholesome green food such as tropical fruits, vegetables,
and tropical cash crops, the deputy said.
</P>
<P>
Also, Hainan will stress the prevention and control of water
and air pollution, step up afforestation, and restore coral reef,
develop ecological tourism and educate the residents to realize
the objective of building an ecological province, Du Qinglin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
