<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Expects Low Inflation, Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- With various economic reform
programs in place, the Philippine government hopes that the
manageable inflation level, the stability of the peso and low
interest rates will continue despite a projected 49.6-billion-peso
(1.24 billion U.S. dollars) budget deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the National Economic and Development
Authority Fellpe Medalla said Saturday that the government expects
the inflation rate to drop to 7.5 percent at the end of this year,
as compared to 9.5 percent last year, which means the rate remains
at a manageable level.
</P>
<P>
"Our projection is that the inflation rate will go down to 7.5
percent," he said in the weekly radio-TV program of President
Joseph Estrada broadcast Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The president and Secretary Benjamin Diokno of the Department
of Budget and Management both said in the program that the
interest rate, which is now 10.3 percent, will continue to go
down, especially now that the country has almost recovered from
the ill effects of the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The president said a stable peso has helped restore investor
confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
"Our investors no longer get nervous because we now have a
stable peso rate at 38 peso to 39 peso to the dollar," the
president noted.
</P>
<P>
Medalla noted that because of the administration's free market
policies and commitment to keeping the Central Bank independent of
the government, the peso has settled at its current rate, which he
said is reasonable enough not to threaten domestic industries
which have to compete with low-priced imported goods.
</P>
<P>
"If the dollar is cheap, that's good because we can buy crude
oil, and other imported goods at low prices. But bringing down the
value of the dollar against the peso at a very low rate is not
good because this will threaten our local businessmen. We think
the 39-40 peso rate is a good balance," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
