<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Go on With Privatization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalami Abubakar said that the Nigerian government is forging
ahead with privatization of the public enterprises despite
opposition of the People's Democratic Party (PDP).
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar said that PDP leaders, like any other
individual, are entitled to their own opinion, but the Nigerian
government will continue with the privatization process, the Post
Express reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the remarks on his way to capital Abuja from
Lagos Friday. He said that the Privatization Committee set up by
the Nigerian government is working on modalities for the process.
</P>
<P>
Senator Anietie Okon, national publicity secretary of the PDP
which won the February 27 presidential election, early this week
asked the current military government to halt the planned
privatization of the sensitive sectors of oil, energy and
telecommunication.
</P>
<P>
Okon said that the PDP is worried about the undue haste with
which the military government is implementing a project of such
fundamental importance to the survival of the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
He explained that privatization cannot be rushed and should not
be conducted in such a manner that would convey the impression
that the exercise is simple to allow some powerful Nigerians
"pocket our national inheritance."  
</P>
</TEXT>
