<HEADLINE> IMF Chief to Visit Nigeria on Debt Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- International Monetary Fund
Director Michel Camdessus is scheduled to visit Nigeria next week
for two-day talks on debt issues and economic reforms, The
Guardian reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an IMF official as saying that Camdessus will
arrive in Nigeria on March 17 and meet government officials over
the implementation of an IMF-backed program signed early this
year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief will also meet IMF officials in the west African
country and hold talks with Nigerian business leaders and heads of
mission from the Group of Seven industrial nations in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He had originally been scheduled in Nigeria in January but
delayed the visit because of the financial crisis in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a western diplomat as saying that the question
of Nigeria's debt burden had been discussed "in negative terms"
last week at a meeting of the Paris Club of international
creditors and further discussions would be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook who visited Nigeria
earlier this week said his government is willing to assist Nigeria
in tackling its debt problem if the in-coming (Olusegun) Obasanjo
government demonstrates a responsible approach to governance.
</P>
<P>
Cook noted that Nigeria's debt management credential had been
severely damaged by the late (Sani) Abacha regime which he said
had refused to pay its due to international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar had since
his assumption of power last June been pleading for a rescheduling
of the country's debt which is estimated at 30 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The west African country is yet to resume debt repayments and
until it does so, and its in-coming civilian government sets out
its economic plans, little movement is expected on the issue,
according to western diplomats involved in debt talks Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
