<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Cashew Nut Union Requests Change of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- An senior official of Mozambique's
National Trade Union of Cashew Nut Industry has urged a change in
export policy concerning unprocessed cashew nuts and an immediate
stop on such export so as to protect the country's cashew nut
processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Guilherme Chavane, general secretary of the union said here
Friday that the three cashew nut processing factory in the capital
Maputo and its environs will soon be paralyzed due to lack of raw
materials and 900 of the total 1,300 staff workers of the
factories, mostly women, are to lose their jobs, the Noticias
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chavane believed that the Mozambican government and the World
Bank should be responsible for the current situation, for under
the latter's pressure, the country implemented a free export
policy regarding unprocessed cashew nuts, which caused bad
consequences to the national industry.
</P>
<P>
The trade union had held several meetings recently to seek for
a way out for the situation. It also made a law draft on the
reviving the cashew nut industry and hoped the draft would soon be
approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is the world's No.1 cashew nut producer, with an
annual output of as high as 390,000 tons. However, the protracted
civil war and lack of management have brought down the production
to 60,000 tons in the recent years, of which about 40,000 tons are
exported while the rest can hardly meet the needs of the 18
processing factories around the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
