<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Implement Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to implement the death penalty to help curb sharply-rising
crimes in the country, the Presidential Secretariat announced
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The government will also follow a more stringent policy in
granting remission of sentences imposed by courts, said a press
release by the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The release said that death penalties will be carried out in
cases of murder and drug-trafficking with the consent of the
judge, the attorney general and the minister of justice.
</P>
<P>
General amnesties will be granted only on the occasion of the
Independence Day instead of on six occasions annually under
current practices, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has death penalty in its law, but has not carried out
an execution since 1956. Death sentences are normally commuted to
life imprisonment by the president.
</P>
<P>
Death penalties commuted to life imprisonment will not be
further reduced to a specific jail term until the prisoner has
served a period of at least 20 years in prison. Nor will the
prisoner be eligible for any remission under general amnesties
till then, the release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that persons convicted of serious crimes such as rape,
child abuse, robbery, unauthorized possession of firearms, acts of
terrorism and drug-trafficking are not eligible for the above
remissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Environmental Problems (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xie noted that more than 80 percent of major polluters in
eastern coastal areas and at least 70 percent of related
operations in central and western regions will be required to meet
waste emission standards by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of pollution control at the nation's
capital Beijing, and urged the municipal government to continue
requiring the use low sulfur coal and clean fuel in a bid to
reduce serious air pollution and substantially improve the local
atmospheric environment by October 1, the 50th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
"Motor vehicles failing to meet state emission standards should
be removed from the capital's roads," said Xie, adding that equal
efforts should be placed on curbing construction dusts and
cleaning rivers.
</P>
<P>
Xie said the government will continue to limit or close mines
producing high sulfur coal in acid rain and sulfur dioxide
pollution control zones, and will ban the construction of new coal-
fired power plants around major cities.
</P>
<P>
Xie also called on environmental departments at all levels to
enhance ecological protection, especially in source areas for
rivers, major lakes and wetlands.
</P>
<P>
"Ecological reserves should be developed in source areas of the
Yellow and Yangtze rivers," said Xie, adding that new damage to
the ecology resulting from the excessive development of mineral,
forest and grassland resources should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
He urged local governments to strengthen monitoring and early
warning systems in ecologically fragile areas.
</P>
<P>
Xie also announced detailed requirements of pollution control
in the Dianchi, Chaohu, Taihu lake areas, as well and the Huaihe,
Haihe, Liaohe river valleys and the Bohai Sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
