<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Border Trade in Southwest China Starts to Pick up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Border trade in southwestern
China is picking up, indicating greater potential for trade with
southeast Asian nations, according to deputies from those regions
to the current session of the Ninth National People's Congress,
the nation's highest lawmaking body.
</P>
<P>
"Border trade in Yunnan went up 76 percent last year, with
export turnover more than double the 1997 figure. We can see from
this fact an optimistic prospect for border trade with neighboring
countries in southeast Asia." said NPC deputy Li Xianwu, a leading
trade official in Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
One year ago, border trade in southwest China plunged as a
result of the southeast Asian financial crisis, which caused
widespread pessimism among Chinese economists about the prospect
of border trade with southeast Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
"Viewing from the current situation in Yunnan, not only border
trade expanded, foreign economic cooperation also rebounded
strongly. Total amount of fund involved in economic cooperation
projects between Yunnan and Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar soared more
than five times last year over 1997," Li Xianwu said.
</P>
<P>
Also, border trade in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region rose by
more than 60 percent last year, according to NPC deputies from the
region. Statistics show that Guangxi's border trade turnover for
the past ten years exceeded three billion yuan, up more than seven
times.
</P>
<P>
Mo Jun, a deputy from Guangxi, said, "Economies of China and
Vietnam are complementary, we export industrial products to
Vietnam and import raw materials from the country. Hence border
trade between the two countries has a very bright prospect in
spite of the plunge in the previous two years as a result of the
Asian financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
Another factor behind the rising border trade was the measures
the Chinese government has taken to promote the trade, which
include readjusting taxes, upgrading infrastructures in border
areas, and eliminating irrational levies, Li Xianwu said, adding
that "provincial governments in southwest China also have stepped
up exploring neighboring markets by all means."
</P>
<P>
"Neighboring countries have also eased restrictions on border
trade in order to lessen their internal economic pressure," he
noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aamodt Tightens Overall Title Fight After Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Kjetil Aamodt picked up
80 points from his second-place finish in Saturday's slalom,
tightening the fight for the overall World Cup season title
against teammate Lasse Kjus at Sierra Nevada, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Alpine ski season will after Sunday's giant slalom with
Kjus leading the overall standings on 1,429 points and Aamodt
trailing at 1,397.
</P>
<P>
Aamodt was timed one minute 50.67 seconds for two runs, just
behind Thomas Stangassinger of Austria in 1:50.44. Italy's Marco
Casanova was third, 1:51.19.
</P>
<P>
Kjus finished 13th in 1:54.05 to get 20 points.
</P>
<P>
Hermann Maier of Austria got no points from his 16th finish and
saw his chance of defending the title evaporated with 1,307 points.
</P>
<P>
Stangassinger won the season's slalom title with 566 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
