<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Parliament Passes Patents Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Parliament passed
the controversial Patents Bill (amendment) Saturday after heated
debates and a three-month delay.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which was passed Friday in Lok Sabha, the lower
house, was approved Saturday by Rajya Sabha, the upper house,
amidst protest walkout by some opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which replaces the Presidential ordinance, was first
passed in Rajya Sabha last December, but it failed to go through
in the Lok Sabha and the government had to make further
amendments.
</P>
<P>
During the heated debate which lasted for four hours Saturday
in Rajya Sabha, Industry Minister Sikander Bakht rejected the
opposition charges that it was against national interests,
explaining that it must be passed before the April 19 deadline to
fulfill the government commitment to the World Trade Organization
(WTO).
</P>
<P>
On Friday, some opposition parties accused the coalition
government of keeping the parliament in dark over crucial
recommendations of the Law Commission, which said the bill
contained certain clauses detrimental to national interests.
</P>
<P>
In its report on February 18, the commission urged the
government to make more amendments to the bill to protect nation
interests.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) has managed to
get support of the main opposition party, the Congress, without
which the bill could not be passed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
