<HEADLINE> G8 to Join in Efforts on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of Cyprus
Ioannis Kasoulides said on Saturday that Cyprus welcomed the Group
of Eight countries (G8) to join in efforts to solve the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
The G8 members is expected to urge the Greek and Turkish sides
to negotiating tables after Turkey's April elections, said the
minister before kicking off a week-long tour to the three European
countries of Germany, Austria and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Any new initiative will be based on previous practices, said
the minister
</P>
<P>
The G8 groups the U.S., Germany, France, Italy, Canada, Japan,
Russia and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island,
but the peace talks between the two sides have been stalled since
summer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is Kasoulides' second European tour this year aimed at
briefing his counterparts and other officials on efforts to
settle the Cyprus issue and to promote the country's bid to join
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in July 1990 and started
substantive talks for accession last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
