<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects All Initiatives on Iraqi Issue: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 13 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi daily newspaper said on
Saturday that Iraq rejects all the initiatives submitted to the
U.N. Security Council on the Iraqi issue and demands the total
lifting of the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial published on Saturday, the daily Babil, owned
by President Saddam Hussein's elder son Udai Saddam, added that
Iraq also rejects the French initiative which, among others, was
forwarded following the mid-December U.S.-British air strikes on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It said that Iraq is not concernd with any amendments to the
French initiative being carried out in the U.N. Security Council,
though some members of the Security Council are trying to press
Iraq to accept the proposal.
</P>
<P>
France in January proposed to the Security Council to only lift
the oil embargo imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invastion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed that a new weapons monitoring regime should
be established to replace the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has voiced its rejection of the French proposal, arguing
that it had not been consulted with it before the initiative was
made.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Russia also put forward initiatives following the
French proposal. The Russian proposal is similar to the French
one.
</P>
<P>
In its initiative, U.S. proposed to allow Iraq to sell as much
oil as its wants to purchase food and medicine for its people,
but insisted on keeping UNSCOM in place.
</P>
<P>
The editorial hailed the Iraqi leadership's stance in
rejecting all those initiatives and insisting on demanding the
total lifting of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council did not agree on any of the
initiatives. After a series of counsultations, however, the
Security Council decided to establish three panels to review all
the aspects of Iraq's relations with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The three panels, which deal with Iraq's disarmament, the
humanitarian situation and the alleged Kuwaiti prisoners of war
and archives respectively, are entitled to make recommendations
to the Council by April 15 on what more needs to be done to
close all the files. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wachter Seeks to Overtake Meissnitzer in Giant Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Anita Wachter was seeking
to overtake teammate Alexandra Meissnitzer in the season's giant
slalom race as she led Saturday's World Cup final women's giant
slalom in Sierra Nevada, Spain.
</P>
<P>
Wachter, who was 84 points behind Meissnitzer on 536, clockd
one minute and 6.37 seconds, followed by Leila Piccard of France (
1:06.76) and Anna Ottosson of Sweden (1:07.68).
</P>
<P>
Meissnitzer, who has won the overall World Cup title and the
Super-G title, finished ninth in 1:08.41.
</P>
<P>
Wachter could win the giant slalom title if she would pick up
100 points for winning the race, and Meissnitzer place outside of
14th. 
</P>
