<HEADLINE> Coastal Afforestation Program Underway in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The implementation of Coastal
Afforestation Program undertaken by the Bangladeshi government at
a cost of 1.23 billion taka (24.7 million U.S. dollars) for all
the 12 coastal districts is progressing, an English daily
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Forest Department (FD) is implementing the program to
create a coastal greenbelt for the protection of the people of the
coastal districts and their property from the cyclonic storm which
visits the areas every year causing damages, the Independent said.
</P>
<P>
The FD has fixed 1,300 kilometers of embankment and 5,096
kilometers of road for afforestation under the program, and set up
150 private nurseries for producing 28 million saplings for
distribution. Besides, it has also taken up the training of 2,100
persons for the implementation of the afforestation program.
</P>
<P>
Now, the FD has decided to bring the premises of educational
institutions, religious institutions, local clubs and the house of
the distressed families, for home tea gardening under the program.
</P>
<P>
However, the report does not mention when the program will be
completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
