<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Outlook Remains Poor in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The labor market deteriorated
in 1998 in Singapore as a result of regional economic crisis and
the employment outlook for this year remains poor as the pace of
recovery in the job market is expected to lag behind that of the
economy, says the Labor Market 1998 Report released Saturday by
the Singapore Ministry of Manpower (MOM).
</P>
<P>
Demand for labor is expected to remain weak in 1999 despite in
recent months market sentiment have improved with the view that
the worst for Asia is over and that a recovery could be seen
possibly in the second half of the year, MOM Permanent Secretary
Tan Chin Nam told a press conference Saturday morning for
releasing the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, total employment in 1998 contracted by
23,384, a sharp reversal from 1997 which saw an overall net
employment gain of 120,280 spread across all sectors. The
full-year decline was the first since the economic recession in
1985/86 in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Total number of persons retrenched in 1998 hit 29,068, nearly
three times the 9,784 retrenched in the previous year and
surpassing the 19,529 laidoffs in the last recession in 1985.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1998, job vacancies averaged 18,342, a
60-percent decline compared with 42,065 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In December 1998, the actual unemployment rate without
adjusting for seasonal factors was 4.6 percent with an estimated
88,700 persons unemployed, reemployment rate of local retrenched
workers dipped to 59 percent form 63 percent in June of the same
year, job openings fell to a new low of 12,630, and there were
only four job openings for every 10 job seekers, a severe drop
from the average of 25 openings in the non-recessionary years in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing employment was the hardest hit contracting by
27,574 in 1998 while the construction sector also registered a net
decline of 4,680 jobs, its first since 1988.
</P>
<P>
However, overall employment in service sectors increased by
8,638, but the employment change within the various services
industries was uneven. Employment shrank in the wholesale and
retail trade, financial institutions, hotel-restaurants as well as
transport and communications, but community and social services
and real estate and business services reported net employment
gains.
</P>
<P>
Tan also said that the MOM has made significant progress in key
areas after it activated manpower action plan six months ago and
launched the 4R initiatives including re-deployment of retrenched
workers, renewal of workforce, realignment of employment practices
and revitalization of employment creation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Closes 38 Insolvent Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Saturday afternoon announced the closure of 38 insolvent banks
while putting seven others under government management.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita at a news
conference at the State Secretary here.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Bambang Subianto, Bank Indonesia Governor
Sabirin and representatives from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), World Bank and Asian Development Bank (ADB) were also
present on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Describing the decision as a decisive step towards
restructuring the private domestic banking system, Ginandjar said
that this is the culmination of months of careful evaluation and
planning, conducted with support from the IMF, World Bank and ADB.
</P>
<P>
"A key objective of these measures is to retain an important
element of private ownership and management in the banking
system," he added.
</P>
<P>
The actions undertaken by the government to deal with the 128
private domestic banks fall into four main groups, according to a
press release.
</P>
<P>
First are category A (with capital adequacy ratio of more than
4 percent) banks, numbering 73. The government has determined that
these banks meet Bank Indonesia's minimum capital adequacy
standards, and can compete effectively without any public
financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
Second are 9 category B (with capital adequacy ratio of between
minus 25 percent and 4 percent) banks that have been determined as
eligible for recapitalization by the government to bring them to
the minimum capital requirements.
</P>
<P>
Capital adequacy ratio is the ratio between capital and
risk-weighted assets.
</P>
<P>
Third are 7 category B banks that have been taken over by the
government Saturday, and fourth are the 38 banks that have been
closed. And the fate of another bank, Bank Ganesha, will be
decided within one week.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Bambang emphasized that these steps are a
significant part of the government's ongoing efforts to establish
a safe, efficient and competitive banking system.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize that it will take some time and considerable
effort to rebuild our banking system, but we are determined to
stay the course," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sabirin reiterated that all deposits in private domestic banks
continue to be guaranteed by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to assure the banking public that these reforms
will in no way affect the safety of their deposits," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government's announcement was due on February 27, but was
postponed for two weeks in an attempt to give banks more chance to
inject fresh cash and revise business plans as well as to provide
the government with ample time to assess the business plans.
</P>
<P>
Banking reform is at the heart of the Indonesian government's
efforts to bring the economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with the IMF, the Indonesian government
closed 16 commercial banks found unhealthy in November 1997. On
April 4 last year, the government froze the operation of seven
private banks and put seven others under the supervision of the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency. Four months later, the
government froze the operation of three banks and took over the
ownership of four other banks.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is organizing a 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout for
Indonesia. The fund has already disbursed some 9 billion dollars
from its own commitment of 11.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to disburse another one billion dollars if its
board of directors approves the letter of intent, which has yet to
be completed by the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar has said that the letter of intent would be submitted
immediately after the launching of the bank restructuring
measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0105 </DOCNO>
