<HEADLINE> Icy Yellow River Section Blown Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese air force planes were
used this morning to blow up the ice blocks in a 22-km section of
the Yellow River in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20 bombs were dropped to blow up the icy section in
Nanhaizi near Baotou City, an industrial base of the region.
</P>
<P>
After the bombing, large ice blocks flowed downstream the river
and the section is expected to melt in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 km long sections of the Yellow River in the region had
remains frozen blocking the flow of ice blocks from the upper
reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Ice on the river has kept melting for the past few days,
although the region is still in grips of a cold spell, leaving
only two sections of ice layer at Sanshengong and Nanhaizi near
Baotou City.
</P>
<P>
The level of obstructed icy water kept rising under the Yellow
River Highway Bridge in Baotou, imposing pressure to the traffic
of a national highway and a nearby power plant. Some parts of the
levee are in danger of overflowing.
</P>
<P>
As a result, China's air force was ordered to implement a
bombard mission last night.
</P>
<P>
The country has been using planes to bombard the ice on the
Yellow River since the 1950s. Icebreakers can't be used, because
the river has a great deal of silting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
