<HEADLINE> Lebanese Army Put on High Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese Army was put on high
alert Friday night after three Israeli helicopter formations
ranged deep into northern and eastern Lebanon, the Voice of the
People radio reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanese Army units observed three Israeli helicopter groups
over Beirut, the Ibrahim River area in north Lebanon and Shmustar
village in the eastern Bekaa," the radio quoted a military source
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter gunships had been joined by warplanes, the
source added.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese troops, mainly anti-aircraft units, were put on
alert to face any possible aggression, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Sources of the United Nations peacekeeping troops stationed in
south Lebanon said that the area under their control in the south
was quiet and no resistance attacks were reported.
</P>
<P>
The heightened tension came hours after Israeli Defense
Minister Moshe Arens termed Lebanon as a "powderkeg" ready to
explode if Hezbollah continue its attacks on Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen, Arens said that "Lebanon, under control of Syria,
has become a powderkeg."
</P>
<P>
"There is no way of telling how far it could escalate if
Hezbollah terrorist actions are not halted," Arens added.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli forces out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, a total of seven Israeli soldiers, including a
general and three officers, were killed in less than a week in
Hezbollah's ambushes.
</P>
<P>
The deadly attacks prompted Israel to launch massive
retaliatory offensives against Hezbollah targets across the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
