"Symphonic Dance" composed by Rachmaninoff (1873-1943) will be
played at the concert. This autobiographic piece of Rachmaninoff,
reflecting a vagabond life the Russian composer led for the rest
of his life, challenges a conductor in technique and artistic
expression as well.
</P>
<P>
"He cries, I cry; he laughs, I laugh," said Lin, "It seems that
I have followed the wondering life of the great master when I
conduct this piece," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Musicians Concert Series were given by the China
National Symphony Orchestra (CNSO) for outstanding Asian musicians
to display their achievements made in symphony. Lin was invited to
one of such concerts by Maestro Chen Zuohuang, CNSO's first
artistic director and conductor.
</P>
<P>
"The CNSO and I have forged good mutual understanding, and we
have had very pleasant cooperation," said Lin, adding that he is
willing to develop the cooperative relations with the national
symphony orchestra, which he believed is the best in current China.
</P>
<P>
Lin cherished the honor to be invited to the concert. He saw
the concert an examination because some of his teachers from the
Central Conservatory of Music would be among the audience.
</P>
<P>
Ten years of studying and living in Russia visualized Lin's
learning on Russian art and culture, which would run into Lin's
imagination when he conducted playing of Russian classic music.
</P>
<P>
"That is why some Russian art critics and audience smelt
Russian smack out of my conducting," said Lin, whose style was
described by Russian media as more Russian than Russian conductors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Let Me Unfold a New World for You": Young Conductor (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I'm just luckier and work harder than others," said Lin, who
has conducted over 300 concerts in European countries including
Russia and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Lin, who received double master's degrees of composing and
conducting as well as a doctoral degree of conducting from Moscow
National Conservatory of Music, conducts mostly playing of
European classic.
</P>
<P>
He tried to introduce some classic Chinese music to Russian
audience. "I found a passionate echo from the audience that was
totally out of my expectation," Lin recalled.
</P>
<P>
Lin has been shuttling back and forth between Moscow and St.
Petersburg for several years, since he was immediately invited to
be assistant conductor for both St. Petersburg Kirov Theater and
St. Petersburg Philharmonic after he won the honor in the contest
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
"I could learn from the masters and even practice by myself,"
Lin said, "it was tough for me to continue study in Moscow and
work in St. Petersburg at the same time, but the experience
benefited me greatly."
</P>
<P>
"I'm only an infant facing world masters," he said.
</P>
<P>
"When a young conductor appears in front of an orchestra, the
first reaction from the orchestra is "what can you do" in most of
the cases," Lin said frankly.
</P>
<P>
By showing what he could do, Lin has been able to gain
authority in front of different orchestras he had cooperation with.
</P>
<P>
"As a conductor, I try my best to interpret what composers want
to express as a translator does. I hope my audience can touch it
in heart through performance of the orchestra," Lin said, who
believes that the most important responsibility of a conductor is
to be loyal to composers.
</P>
<P>
"Music changes in the twinkling of eyes, and my heart responds,
" he said, "I have been entirely melted into music."
</P>
<P>
Every time I conduct, I feel like that I open a window which
enables audience and I to view a completely new world," Lin said,
"the more I see, the more enriched I will be."
</P>
<P>
Lin hoped that he would be able to find an ideal job in China
so as to join people in making contributions to popularization of
symphony in China, which he believed needs more people to devote
to.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions are much better than those of two decades ago,"
he said, "I'm confident that more Chinese will be fond of classic
music in the future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Suspend All Allegedly Corrupt Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) --Tanzania has decided to
suspend all the civil servants who are alleged by the public to be
corrupt as the ongoing anti-graft war intensifies in the country.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers here Saturday quoted Wilson Masilingi, minister of
state in the president's office, as saying that no government
officials, such as village and ward executives, magistrates,
police, and commercial officers in districts and regions are
exempted from the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Masilingi told a press conference Friday that relevant
authorities will continue with investigations while the suspended
officials are out of office.
</P>
<P>
He cited an example that 85 officials in the Ministry of Health
who are allegedly connected with corrupt practices will be sent
under investigation by the Preventive of Corruption Bureau (PCB).
</P>
<P>
Masilingi said the government will send one PCB official to
every region to assist local administration in fighting against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"The government has already recruited a number of trained
youths in various disciplines to work with the bureau as well as
the state intelligence unit and the police force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Masilingi revealed that PCB is investigating officials of the
Ministry of Lands and Human Settlements in Coast Region who
allegedly offered the coast regional commissioner a plot in a
restricted area.
</P>
<P>
"The construction has been suspended and investigations are
proceeding... When established there is corruption all will go
even if it is a regional commissioner," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
