<HEADLINE> Germany Increases Aid to Jordan in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany has decided to provide to
Jordan 8 million Deutsche marks (some 38 million U.S. dollars) in
financial and technical aid in 1999, an eight percent increase
over 1998, the semiofficial Jordan Times reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The aid package will be divided into two parts: 32 million
dollars in loans mainly to be used for water and waste water
projects, and the remaining 5.6 million dollars are grants in
technical assistance, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has also agreed to swap 28 million dollars in
Jordanian debts in 1999, bringing up to 100.4 million dollars the
total debt swap granted in the last few years, the paper quoted
German embassy's Charge d'affaires Mathias Ohne Mueller as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The package will cover such sectors as water, agriculture,
environment, information systems and institutional support
systems, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is one of the main European donors of the desert
kingdom, and has provided Jordan 951 million dollars in soft loans
and grants between 1962 and 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
