<HEADLINE> China's Production of Energy Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China suffered an annual drop of
3.8 percent in the production of energy last year, according to
figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total energy output in 1998 stood at 1.223 billion tons of
standard coal equivalent, of which 120 million tons were produced
in December, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Production of coal dropped 5.5 percent to 1.236 billion tons,
that of crude oil dipped 0.1 percent to 162.6 million tons and
that of natural gas dropped by 0.6 percent to 22.3 billion cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the output of electricity increased by 2.7 percent
to 1.14 trillion kwh. In a breakdown, it consisted of 929 billion
kwh of thermal power, up 1.8 percent; 195 billion kwh of hydro-
electric power, up 5.6 percent; and 14.1 billion kwh of nuclear
power, down 2.1 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
