<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Anti-Malaria Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A new multi-sectoral malaria
project has been launched in Kenya to raise knowledge and
awareness about the tropical killer disease in the government
effort to curb the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The one-year project, with a fund of 75,000 U.S. dollars
provided by Becton Dickinson, an American-based manufacturing
firm, will be administered by the Kenya Medical Research
Institute, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr John Ouma from the Health Ministry, malaria
kills about 72 Kenyan children daily while another one million
people of all ages in the country are afflicted by the tropical
scourge annually.
</P>
<P>
It is said that malaria mainly prevails in the areas along the
Lake Victoria in western Kenya and that in the east coast.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony here Friday, Julius Meme,
director of Medical Services Department under the Health Ministry,
said the new project was aimed at promoting the multi-sectoral
partnership in the war against the tropical scourge.
</P>
<P>
The director said more than 30 percent of patients seeking
treatment at health institutions across the country were
suffering from malaria.
</P>
<P>
The new anti-malaria project, he said, would strengthen the
ministry's Malaria Control Unit in coordinating and supervising
its control activities, increasing the rate of reporting and flow
of data and improving the knowledge of the affected communities
on control the tropical killer disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
