<HEADLINE> HK Citizens Urged to Plant Trees in Country Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Members of the public were
urged Saturday to take part in a community tree-planting scheme in
support of enhancing a green countryside in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by the chairman of Country and Marine Parks
Board (CMPB), Dr Tam Wing-kun, at the launching ceremony for this
year's scheme.
</P>
<P>
As a keen supporter of the event since the 1980's, Tam said he
was delighted with the encouraging response Agriculture and
Fisheries Department (AFD) of Hong Kong received this year, as
more than 20,000 applicants had been enrolled in the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Tam said AFD had planted more than 1.8 million tree seedlings
in the past five years and more than 40 percent of these were
local species.
</P>
<P>
He said AFD would enhance the territory's afforestation plan in
the coming year, with the objective of developing a countryside
with richer species and more diversified habitats.
</P>
<P>
"According to this year's plan, the number of tree species will
be increased in order to provide better habitats for wildlife," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the ceremony, Director of Agriculture and
Fisheries Lessie Wei said that about 10 local corporations would
plant some 100,000 tree seedlings under this year's Corporate
Afforestation Scheme.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from efforts of the government, we need support from all
sectors of the community," Wei said. 
</P>
