<HEADLINE> Kenya Starts Road Rehabilitation Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has launched a nation-wide
road rehabilitation project with a loan of 5.9 billion shillings
(about 92.5 million U.S. dollars) in a bid to restore the roads
destroyed by the 1997 El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
Some 4.9 billion shillings came from the World Bank and the
rest from the African Development Bank, major Kenyan newspapers
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the launch of the El Nino Emergency Project (ENEP)
Friday in Mombasa, a port city bordering the Indian Ocean,
Minister of State Julius Ole Sunkuli said the loan for the project
covered only 40 percent of the rehabilitation costs, while the
rest of the money will be drawn from a fuel levy fund and from
other development partners.
</P>
<P>
The repairs will give priority to roads, bridges and drainage
systems in 36 districts and seven urban centers identified as the
worst affected, Sunkuli said, adding the repair works will
commence countrywide within three months and Mombasa will have 45
kilometers of damaged roads repaired.
</P>
<P>
He warned domestic and foreign road contractors that the
Kenyan government will not accept shoddy work in road
rehabilitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
