<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Raw Materials in China Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The latest figures from the
National Bureau of Statistics show that China's raw materials
prices continued to drop in November last year.
</P>
<P>
The general price index of all raw materials as a whole stood
at 93.89 in November 1998, down from 100 for the same month in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The price index of non-ferrous metal materials and electric
wire dropped to 85.16, representing the biggest decrease in price.
</P>
<P>
Prices of timber and paper pulp rebounded in November with a
price index of 107.22, the highest of all raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Experts have predicted that the prices of raw materials may
rebound gradually now that the government has taken measures to
increase investment in infrastructure construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Govt Wins Battle over Bankruptcy Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The long-brewed bankruptcy bill
in Thailand cleared the Parliament Friday night, after the Senate
heeded government pleas to keep harsh measures intact.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the bill is seen not only as a victory for the
government, but more importantly, a necessary step leading to a
smooth economic recovery, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcy bill, one of the essential parts of the
financial reform package crucial to Thailand's economic recovery,
was drawn by the government and put to the Senate on Friday for
the final reading.
</P>
<P>
But earlier, a vetting committee of the Senate had suggested
some drastic amendments to the draft bill, aiming to offer
increased protection to borrowers against creditors.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes would prevent creditors from filing
bankruptcy cases if pledged collateral was sufficient to cover any
outstanding debt. Guarantors would not be held responsible if a
bankruptcy case was filed against borrowers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a borrower held by the courts to be bankrupt would
have his record cleared after one year. The committee also
proposed to protect at least 100,000 baht (2,702 U.S. dollars) in
personal assets and the homes of bankrupt borrowers.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes were rejected by the government, which
argued that accepting the changes would destroy the credit system
and aggravate problems faced by the financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Thai financial system is laboring under the weight of
non-performing loans of more than 2.7 trillion baht (72.9 billion
dollars), or more than 45 percent of total outstanding credit.
</P>
<P>
Pending the final vote on Friday, business leaders and major
newspapers voiced support to the government.
</P>
<P>
Chairmen of the Thai Bankers' Association, the Federation of
Thai Industries and the Board of Trade in Thailand issued a joint
statement supporting the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bangkok Post and the Nation, two major English
newspapers, said in their Friday comments that the vetting
committee's proposals were unacceptable because it would destroy
"a culture of responsibility in which people are accountable for
their business decisions and contracts," and it would also destroy
"a culture under which loans must be repaid otherwise the
financial system would fall apart."
</P>
<P>
The firm stances adopted by both the government and the Senate
vetting committee had created a deadlock before the vote Friday,
as each side was trying to hold the other responsible for
rejecting compromise.
</P>
<P>
However, compromises were reached in Friday's vote when the
government agreed to accept the amnesty for persons discharged
from bankrupt status, but increased the one-year waiting period to
three years.
</P>
<P>
The government also agreed to increase the lowest amount of
debt liable for bankruptcy action to one million baht (27,027
dollars) for ordinary persons and two million baht (54,054 dollars
for legal entities, as proposed by the vetting committee.
</P>
<P>
At last, senators voted 162-1 with one abstention to pass the
bill in the final reading.
</P>
<P>
The bill will have to go back to the House of Representatives
because changes were made, but the lower chamber looks certain to
agree with all the changes before the bill becomes law.
</P>
<P>
Together with the foreclosure bill passed earlier Friday and a
bill to establish a bankruptcy court adopted two weeks ago, the
financial reform package has now cleared the legislative hurdle.
</P>
<P>
But it also means that there is little excuse left in the
legislative area for the government to seek when trying to bring
the country's economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda confidently predicted a
bottoming-out of the economy this year with some positive signs
emerging next month.
</P>
<P>
He is planning to jump-start the economy through a 53 billion
baht (1.45 billion dollar) state spending program and a tax cut
package.
</P>
<P>
However, both Thai economists and foreign agencies considered
Tarrin's prediction too optimistic, taking into account the lack
of team work, delays in disbursing funds into real sector and the
worsening banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, The passage of the bankruptcy bill and other key
economic bills gives a big boost to the government' reform
efforts, although it at the same time poses greater challenges for
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai and his economic team, analysts said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
