<HEADLINE> Retail Sales of China's State-Owned Shops Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned retailers
sold 602 billion yuan (72.7 billion U.S. dollars) worth of
consumer goods in 1998, a drop of 5.3 percent from 1997, said the
National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the bureau also show that total retail sales value
of consumer goods in the country increased by 6.8 percent to 2.9
trillion yuan (352 billion U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Private owned sector saw the highest annual rise of 26 percent
with a retail sales value of 139 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Retailers funded by foreign investment also recorded a hefty
growth of 22.2 percent with their sales value hitting 22.6 billion
yuan, while sales value of retailers funded by investment from
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan grew by 7.6 percent to 21.6 billion
yuan, according to the bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
