<HEADLINE> China's Production of Cigarettes Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China produced fewer cigarettes
in 1998 than the previous year, according to the National Bureau
of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The output of cigarettes last year stood at 33.6 million cases,
dipping 0.1 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies show that cigarettes now claim 2,000 lives in
China every day and the number is expected to climb to 8,000 per
day by the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
An anti-smoking campaign is going on in China, and the
government has been striving to ban smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest tobacco producer and home of 320
million smokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 60 Percent of Arrests in India Unjustifiable: Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Sixty percent of all arrests by
the police in India were "unnecessary and unjustifiable", chairman
of the National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) Justice M. N.
Venkatachaliah said Friday.
</P>
<P>
These accounted for 43 percent of the total expenditure
incurred by prisons, the NHRC leader said while addressing a group
of district and sessions judges and officers from correctional
services.
</P>
<P>
In Delhi's Tihar Jail, according to the Times of India
Saturday, only 10 to 15 percent of the inmates were convicts, the
rest being under trials.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted Venkatachaliah as saying that most of the
complaints reaching the NHRC relate to the police and it was
reportedly said that even innocent people with mental disabilities
were sometimes being held in prisons.
</P>
<P>
"There is a very low rate of conviction as the investigations
carried out leave much to be desired," he said. "The degree of
acquittals is very demoralizing for the public as the offenders
get away scot-free."
</P>
<P>
According to the just released NHRC annual report, the rate of
acquittals, particularly in heinous offenses, is "almost 80
percent" and the delays in trials have now become proverbial".
</P>
<P>
He suggested that plea bargaining be introduced in India,
saying that it was a very effective means of reducing the workload
on the criminal justice administration in most Western countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
