<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Build One More Drug Control Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has laid
the foundation to build another drug abuse control museum in
Laukkai, Kokang Region of Myanmar's Shan state, to mark
eradication of opium in the state and to educate its people
against the danger of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
The cornerstone was laid Thursday by First Secretary of the
Myanmar State Peace and Development Council Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt, the official New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The museum will ensure long-term benefit for the people as it
will exhibit the arrival of poppy cultivation in Myanmar, evil
consequences of the narcotic drugs and drug eradication efforts
which will help eliminate the illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
The first Myanmar drug abuse control museum has been under
construction here since last July.
</P>
<P>
During the period from 1988 to 1998, the Myanmar authorities
seized a total of 4,125.31 kilos of heroin along with 28,385.89
kilos of opium, 281.6 kilos of morphine, 6,606 kilos of marijuana,
33,807.8 liters of phensedyl and 26.96 million of stimulant
tablets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
