<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldovan New Government Wins Vote of Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Moldova's parliament Friday
approved, by a tight vote of 52 to 50, the seventh cabinet headed
by Ion Sturza and its platform, which heralded an end to the
republic's month-old political crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, the vote of confidence has been won not as a result of
the settlement of the disputes over the assignment of ministerial
posts within the ruling coalition, but because of a critical vote
gained through technical means.
</P>
<P>
The decisive vote came from deputy Ilie Ilascu, imprisoned in
the Moldovan break-away region of Trans-Dniester since 1992 for
alleged terrorism. Ilascu sent his favorable vote for the new
government from prison by mail.
</P>
<P>
His vote was decisive because the Constitutional Court refused
to validate parliament's approval of Sturza by 51-50 last week,
deeming it unconstitutional and sending the move back for another
vote.
</P>
<P>
Moldovan President Petru Lucinschi nominated Sturza as prime
minister on February 19 and again on March 9. The parliament
rejected the first nomination by 101 to 51 votes.
</P>
<P>
On the second nomination, the president urged the parliament to
make a compromise to pave the way for the forming of the
government and threatened to dismiss the parliament for early
elections if the new government was vetoed again.
</P>
<P>
Lucinschi is due to approve the new cabinet later in the day.
The new government will be sworn in right after the approval.
</P>
<P>
Sturza, 38, served as the deputy prime minister in the last
cabinet in charge of economic affairs. The president believed he
would be capable of steering the country out of the current
economic crisis because the new premier understands the country's
economic well-being and has a good rapport with international
financial bodies.
</P>
<P>
Moldova is beset with severe financial and economic
difficulties. It currency, the leu, lost half of its value in 24
hours in November after the central bank said it would not prop it
up.
</P>
<P>
Inflation hit 18.3 percent in 1998 and is expected to slip to
about 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Former premier Ion Ciubuc resigned last month amid differences
with his ministers on the pace and degree of economic reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
