<HEADLINE> Norway to Further Cut Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Minister of Oil and
Energy Marit Arnstad said on Friday that his country was ready to
reduce its oil production to back the international move to prop
up oil prices by curtailing oil output.
</P>
<P>
Arnstad made the remark in Oslo after energy ministers from
four member countries of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) -- Algeria, Iran, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela, as
well as non-OPEC Mexico agreed to cut oil output after two days of
negotiations at the Hague meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian minister, however, made no specific commitments,
as any move to cut oil production in the country must be first
approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Last spring, Norway decided to reduce its daily oil production
from the North Sea oil fields by 100,000 barrels by the end of
1998 to support the world oil producers' bid to limit oil output.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, the oil production cut was extended to
this coming summer.
</P>
<P>
Norway is the largest oil producer in western Europe and the
second largest oil exporter in the world, with an annual output of
oil and natural gas of 200 million tons in oil equivalent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
