<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Approves Energy Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's National Assembly
approved Friday the principles of a national strategy for the
development of the energy sector until 2010.
</P>
<P>
Following a five-hour debate, 197 parliament members voted in
favor and four abstained -- two from the Bulgarian Socialist Party
(BSP) and two from the Alliance for National Salvation (ANS).
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor, representatives of all the parliamentary
groups also supported the stance of the government that units one
to four of the Kozlodoui nuclear power plant, on the Danube,
should be decommissioned after the expiry of their service life
and after the construction of replacement facilities.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been demanding Bulgaria shut down the
four units of the Kozlodoui nuclear power plant in line with a
1993 agreement signed between the two sides, saying Bulgaria
should fulfill the demand before it becomes an EU member.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, however, repeatedly rejected the EU's demand on
grounds that the decommissioning of the four units will cost
Bulgaria a large amount of money and it cannot finance the
decommissioning projects since the money promised by the EU for
the decommissioning has not been received yet.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian parliament on Friday mandated the Government to
open talks with the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development (EBRD), the European Commission and other
international institutions and to negotiate mutually acceptable
terms and conditions for meeting the commitments assumed in regard
to the power industry.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian cabinet will have to adopt a technological plan,
supported by a concrete financial program, for upgrading units
five and six of the Kozlodoui Nuclear plant and rehabilitating
several thermoelectric power stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
