<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Industrial Production Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's index of
industrial production (IIP) for January 1999 dropped by 11.2
percent compared with the same period of last year, the Statistics
Department said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The IIP for January 1999, which stood at 134.7, also fell 8.9
percent compared with the index of 147.8 for December 1998,
according to the department's IIP figures released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The lower index for January this year from a year earlier was
attributed solely to the drop of 15.7 percent in the manufacturing
division index to 133.5 from 158.3.
</P>
<P>
Among a total of 23 major groups in the manufacturing division,
only two -- footwear and industrial chemicals -- recorded higher
indices for January 1999, while the remaining 21 groups registered
lower indices.
</P>
<P>
The IIP for the mining division and the electricity division
rose by 1.7 percent to 129.5 and by 0.7 percent to 161.6
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the mining index was due to the rise in the
indices of tin and natural gas while the higher index in the
electricity division was due to the 0.7 percent growth in the
generation of electricity to 4,591 million kilowatt-hours (1999)
from 4,560 million kilowatt-hours (1998).
</P>
<P>
The IIP is a measure of the rate of change in the production of
industrial commodities in real terms over time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
