<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Pleased with Central American Trade Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican government is
satisfied with the Central American treaty on the solution of
trade disputes signed Thursday in Guatemala by the ministers of
economy and foreign trade of Guatemala, El Salvador and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Foreign Trade Minister Samuel Guzowski said Friday
that the signing of the treaty is a milestone in the Central
American integration process.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica started a campaign last May to conclude a treaty on
this matter to achieve an effective modernization of the scheme of
Central American economic integration, said Guzowski.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, he said, the isthmus governments and
private sectors will have "a juridical mechanism to resolve
commercial controversies out of the political agencies, following
a rapid, secure and foreseeable procedure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Guzowski said that the treaty is an important contribution to
the strengthening of the rule of law in Central America.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, along with the Regulation of Measures of
Normalization, Metrology, and Authorization Processing and
Regulations of Measures and Sanitary and Phytosanitary Procedures,
will be signed in the near future by Honduras and Nicaragua, whose
ministers did not attend the meeting held Thursday in Guatemala.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Urged to Relax Money Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Economic Planning Secretary Felipe
Medalla said the Philippine Central Bank should provide room for
further monetary expansion to achieve at least a 2.6-percent
growth in gross domestic product this year, a local newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Medalla was quoted by Philippine Daily Inquirer as saying that
the attainment of the growth target would largely depend on
whether loan growth would pick up to stimulate more economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank should be more expansionary at this time
because I'm worried about the lending numbers," Medalla said.
</P>
<P>
He said loan growth in December last year, for instance, slowed
down by 4.8 percent compared to year-ago levels. If loan growth
fails to pick up this quarter, Medalla said, the country might not
hit its growth targets this year.
</P>
<P>
"We can either downscale it or work harder to attain it through
more reform measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
One reform measure which should be accelerated to perk up
economic growth was the liberalization of retail trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the central bank should exercise further
moral suasion to encourage banks to be more aggressive in lending,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Under the macroeconomic program with the International Monetary
Fund, the central bank will allow domestic liquidity to grow by 15
percent this year compared to last year's 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank has lowered its internal ceiling for
this year to 13.9 percent to ensure that there would be no excess
liquidity that could exert pressure on inflation or be used by
banks to speculate against the peso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
