<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Oil Output Cut to Stabilize Market: Mexican Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Energy Minister Luis
Tellez said Friday the new oil output cut agreed on with Saudi
Arabia, Iran, Algeria and Venezuela of more than two million
barrels a day will stabilize the world market and slightly raise
the price.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of energy of the five major oil producing
countries agreed at a meeting held in The Hague to reduce by two
million barrels a day their daily crude output starting April 1.
</P>
<P>
It was not known how much each country will reduce its
production.
</P>
<P>
Tellez said that the oil producing countries reduced the supply
of oil by 3.1 million barrels a day in 1998, a measure that
stopped the drop of the international prices, which reached their
lowest levels of the last 22 years.
</P>
<P>
This effort achieved a slight and brief price recovery, but it
dropped again because of the persistence and the worsening of the
international financial crisis in the second half of 1998, said
Tellez.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (
OPEC) will announce their production cuts during the organization'
s next meeting on March 23 in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Tellez said Mexico's crude supply cut will be announced before
April 1.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is a major oil producer and exporter, producing some
three million barrels per day of crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
