<HEADLINE> Peru Reinforces Watch Along Border With Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian Defense Minister Gen. Julio
Salazar Monroe Friday announced that the Peruvian armed forces
have reinforced 17 border surveillance posts to check infiltration
of Colombian guerrillas and drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Salazar told the press upon his return from the border region
that more military and police posts had been created in the
Peruvian border village of El Estrecho, on the Putumayo River
banks.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian press has denounced recently intensified
activities of Colombian drug traffickers and loggers in Peruvian
Amazonia.
</P>
<P>
Colombia and Peru share a 1,600-kilometer-long border, of which
a natural line is the Putumayo River.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian defense minister said that the troops sent to
reinforce the Peru-Colombia border were retired from the border
with Ecuador and that some of them had been concentrated in a
military base in the jungle town of Iquitos, some 1,600 kilometers
northeast of Lima.
</P>
<P>
The minister inspected the reinforcement of the border,
accompanied by Interior Minister Julio Villanueva and advisor to
the National Intelligence Service Vladimiro Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said the movement of the Peruvian forces was ordered
some weeks ago by President Alberto Fujimori "to counter the
advance of Colombian terrorists and drug traffickers." 
</P>
