<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 500,000 Child Laborers in Sri Lanka: ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- There are nearly 500,000 child
laborers in Sri Lanka and about 10,000 are living permanently on
the streets, said the International Labor Organization (ILO) in
its latest report.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed at a seminar held recently in Colombo to
deliberate on the ratification of Convention No.138 which
stipulates the minimum age of 15 years for admission for
employment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting recent statistics of government and
non-governmental sectors and organizations, said the common forms
of child labor seen in Sri Lanka are domestic employment,
involuntary begging on the streets, child prostitution, work in
the informal sector and work in the tourist fishing and gemming
industries.
</P>
<P>
The number of child laborers in the 10 to 14 age group has
gradually decreased in recent years. In 1990, over 80,000 children
were employed while in 1998 it dropped to 39,000.
</P>
<P>
There are about 30,000 child prostitutes, according to national
and international estimates, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sri Lankan law, no child under 14 could be
employed in industry or commerce and no child under 12 could be
employed in domestic service.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka was among the first 27 fully participating countries
in the ILO's International Program for the Elimination of Child
Labor.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the minimum age convention is one of the
key measures proposed by the ILO to combat the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel Group ELN Denies Assassinations Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian National Liberation
Army (ELN) guerrilla group Friday denied any involvement in a
recent spate of assassinations and kidnappings over the border
with Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen of ELN, the second largest rebel group in Columbia
after the Revolutionary Armed Forces (FARC), contacted the El
Universal newspaper specifically to deny any involvement in the
abduction of a Venezuelan cattleman, Eudes Acosta, saying he must
have been taken in the state of Zulia by the common criminals who
committed the crime in the name of the ELN.
</P>
<P>
They also ruled out any part in the attack which occurred
Tuesday night in Guasdalito, a village in the state of Apura.
</P>
<P>
The attack, conducted by eight armed men dressed in civilian
clothes, caused an intense military mobilization in the air and on
land.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have expressed their willingness to collaborate with
the Venezuelan authorities investigating the crimes.
</P>
<P>
They said that the ELN Central Command would not attack
Venezuelan installations, military elements, or border bases near
the Colombian territories where they have influence.
</P>
<P>
They repeated their willingness not to commit kidnappings on
the Venezuelan soil. "We have canceled military activities on your
territory," the ELN spokesmen told El Universal.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, ambassadors from the European Union and other
countries in Bogota called for an end to the killing of foreigners
by guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
A senior commander of the FARC Wednesday said that a local
squad leader acted without his superior's knowledge or approval in
abducting and executing three U.S. citizens earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
