<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Zealand-Australian Joint Currency not on Agenda:PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley said on Saturday that a joint New Zealand-Australian
currency is not on the agenda of the prime ministerial taskforce
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A media release issued by the New Zealand Prime Minister's
Office said the Auckland-based New Zealand Herald Saturday
"incorrectly quoted the Prime Minister as saying the taskforce
would look beyond the issues" outlined by Shipley and her
Australian counterpart John Howard during the latter's visit to
New Zealand last month.
</P>
<P>
During Howard's visit to New Zealand, The two prime ministers
decided to establish a New Zealand- Australian taskforce to sort
out issues outstanding from the Closer Economic Relations Trade
Agreement (CER) between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the CER agreement was signed in 1983, New
Zealand-Australian trade has increased by 275 percent with their
trade standing at 5.4 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper implied that a controversial issue on a New
Zealand-Australian joint currency, which has recently been
discussed in New Zealand media, is on the agenda of the taskforce.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a currency taskforce. A joint currency is not on
the agenda," Shipley said in the release.
</P>
<P>
She said the taskforce would focus on barriers and costs to
trans-Tasman investment and some other issues, and also examine
future directions for CER, including further steps within CER to
strengthen economic ties, and extending CER's links with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The strengthening of economic ties within CER does not include
"consideration of a joint currency," Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
"A unified currency is not being considered," she said. "I have
 always said I see no reason why we should consider it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
