<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blatter Calls for Changes in Soccer World Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- FIFA president Sepp Blatter said
his organization will have a radically revised world calendar by
2005 with fewer domestic matches and better coordination of
international play.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said international competition would run through a
calendar year, with events starting in February and being finished
by the end of November, a contrast to the traditional European
season, which begins its league and cup competitions in July-
August and conclude in May.
</P>
<P>
The changes should put an end to problems national teams
gathering a full squad for matches or tournaments because of
conflicts with club schedules.
</P>
<P>
Domestic leagues, which include up to 20 clubs in England and
Spain, would be reduced to 16 teams each. About 44 weeks would be
set aside for up to two games a week, and it would be specified
which dates are available for domestic league and cup competition,
continental club championships and international matches.
</P>
<P>
However, Blatter said the plans would not stop individual
countries from holding their cup competitions when they wanted.
</P>
<P>
Continental championships would take place in even-numbered
years, Blatter said. Some, such as the South American event, are
presently held in odd-numbered years.
</P>
<P>
December would be a month when "everyone will put their feet up
", while January would be available for preparation and some
matches, such as the planned World Club Championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
