<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jet Violates Accord, Flying Near Cable Car: Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. jet which killed 20
tourists in the Italian Alps last February should not have been in
the air at all under the Italy-NATO accord of 1997, Italian
military investigators said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, only flights of F-16 fighter bombers
were authorized in the area of the accident, the Mt. Cermis ski
resort in the Dolomites in northeastern Italy.
</P>
<P>
Italian military investigators said that prowler military
reconnaissance jets like the one piloted by Marine Captain Richard
Ashby, acquitted of negligence last week, were supposed by the
accord to move their training missions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ashby's jet also broke all the rules on such flights, which set
a minimum altitude of 600m, but Ashby hit the ski-lift cable at
about 100m above the ground, said the investigators.
</P>
<P>
Italian judicial sources said it was possible that a new
indictment might be sought by Italian prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residents near the NATO Aviano air base Friday urged
the government to ban all flights in the surrounding alpine
valleys.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers acting for the victims' families also wrote a letter on
Friday to Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema urging him to see that "
the killer pilot remain silent" after what they took as "insincere
apologies" issued since he was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
In Warsaw, during his visit to Poland Friday, D'Alema repeated
his demand for justice to be done.
</P>
<P>
"If justice does not come, Italy will press for a revision of
the 1951 London Convention which assigned jurisdiction in such
cases to the home nation of the NATO personnel," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
