<HEADLINE> China's Transportation Peak Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's transportation sector has
handled more than 1.5 billion passengers during the 40-day "Spring
Festival Travel Period", which has always witnessed the country's
largest population flow in a year.
</P>
<P>
The passenger volume was up 3.1 percent on an annual basis in
the travel season that started from February 1st to March 12,
according to the release from the State Economic and Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The festival is the most important one for Chinese people, when
people head home for family reunions or migrate to urban areas to
find jobs.
</P>
<P>
Demand of all transportation means was strong, except the water-
bound, whose volume dropped by 13 percent to 27 million.
</P>
<P>
The railway transportation witnessed an 8.2 percent increase of
passenger volume to 123 million and those by travel buses peaked 1.
397 billion, representing a surge of three percent. The civil
aviation sector saw the biggest growth margin of 10.8 percent and
it handled 6.65 million trips.
</P>
<P>
There were more people spending their one week-long Spring
Festival holiday traveling this year, which substantially boosted
the passenger volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadorian President Unveils Austerity Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadorian President Jamil Mahuad
Friday announced a series of strict measures to raise revenues
with new taxes and to ensure that the wealthy pay their taxes in a
bid to relieve the country's worst financial crisis in decades.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after the board of directors of Ecuador's
Central Bank resigned Thursday as a nationwide strike protesting
the government's economic policies entered the second day.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank President Luis Jacome, who also quit his post, had
been under attack for allowing Ecuador's currency, the sucre, to
float last month, causing its value to dive sharply by 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
Banks across the country remained shut for the fourth day in a
row after President Mahuad ordered an emergency bank holiday to
prevent mass withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, police have arrested 235 demonstrators,
using tear gas to disperse protesters, while the government
imposed a 48-hour state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators, led by Ecuador's trade unions, want the
government to change its austerity economic measures, announced by
Mahuad last September, which include fuel subsidy cuts and a wage
freeze.
</P>
<P>
The government's political opponents have accused Jacome of ill-
implementing Ecuador's fiscal policy and criticized Mahuad of
acting too slowly to right the economy.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador is locked in its worst economic crisis in recent
decades, caused by low oil prices and floods resulting from El
Nino last year. Oil is the country's major hard currency earner.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's inflation is running near 50 percent, the highest in
Latin America, and its currency lost a quarter of its value last
week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
