<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Commission Recommends Expulsion, Warning against Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The IOC ad hoc Commission
investigating the conduct of certain IOC members on Friday
recommended severe punishments against those accused of improper
conduct arising from the Salt Lake City Olympic bid process.
</P>
<P>
In a press released received here on Saturday, the six-member
commission headed by vice president Dick Pound of Canada, said in
its second report that it has examined the conduct of 17 IOC
members as the 18th member Charles Mukora of Kenya resigned from
the IOC and was not included in the final report.
</P>
<P>
The commission confirmed its previous recommendations that five
IOC members be excluded from the organization, namely Agustin C.
Arroyo of Ecuador, Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir of Sudan, Jean-
Claude Ganga of Congo, Lamine Keita of Mali and Sergio Santander
Fantini of Chile.
</P>
<P>
It further recommended one additional expulsion against Paul
Wallwork of Samoa.
</P>
<P>
Based upon the evidence presented in the investigation, the
commission also recommended warnings or varying degrees of
severity by the IOC Executive Board against nine IOC members
including Un Yong Kim of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The other eight members are Phillip Walter Coles of Australia,
Louis Guirandou-N'Diaye of Ivory Coast, Willi Kaltschmitt Lujan of
Guatemala, Shagdarjav Magvan of Mongolia, anani Matthia of Togo,
Austin Sealy of Barbados, Vitaly Smirnov of Russia and Mohamed
Zerguini of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The commission also recommended that three members be
exonerated of the allegations made against them and were cleared
of misconduct, they are Henry Edmund Olefemi Adefope of Nigeria,
Ashwini Kumar of India and Ram Ruhee of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
In the report's conclusions, the commission stated that "the
commission fully recognizes that the IOC must take action. The
commission is aware that the IOC is prepared to do so. The IOC
must also implement reforms to ensure that these types of problems
never occur again."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commission called on bid cities and National
Olympic Committees to do a better job of following the rules
specifically outlined in all bid city documents.
</P>
<P>
"Bidding cities are entitled to expect more guidance in these
matters from their National Olympic Committees. They should not be
left more or less on their own in the process. At the same time,
the IOC acknowledges that it could have put in place more
effective controls from its own perspective to monitor the
situation," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the recommendations for actions against certain
members, the commission also reaffirmed its endorsement of reforms
it put forth in its initial report on January 24. These included
adoption of significant changes in the host city election process,
limitations on travel by IOC members to bid cities and the
creation of a permanent, independent Ethics Commission.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations for expulsion, which have gone to the IOC
Executive Board, will be presented to the full IOC membership
which will be meeting in extraordinary session on March 17-18 in
Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the IOC's membership must vote to exclude a
member, who has the right to speak before the full session. And it
is unclear at the moment as to how many of the five members who
are facing expulsion will be speaking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0196 </DOCNO>
