<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECB Head Raps Euroland Governments Over Public Finances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Wim Duisenberg, president of the
European Central Bank (ECB), rapped Euroland governments Friday
for letting public finances drift away from the guidelines set for
European economic and monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Rome at a conference organized by British weekly
The Economist, the head of ECB urged governments to implement the
structural measures necessary to keep spending under control in
the medium and long term.
</P>
<P>
"A rigid application of the Pact for Stability and Growth by
each of the euro area's member countries is essential," Duisenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
"Progress in trimming euro area budgets has not been
sufficiently consolidated," he added, pointing out that public
debt was still too high and budget deficits were too close to the
limit of three percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
In reference to calls from politicians for an interest rate cut
to boost Euroland's flagging economy and help create jobs,
Duisenberg said unemployment should be tackled with flexibility in
labor markets and precisely targeted incentives.
</P>
<P>
Countries such as the Netherlands, Ireland, Portugal and
Austria had been able to contain rising unemployment thanks to
their highly flexible labor markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg also urged Euroland governments to counter slow
growth with action instead of words.
</P>
<P>
"If governments shoulder their responsibilities and respect the
tasks and objectives set in the Maastricht Treaty, they will be
making the best possible contribution to guarantee the euro area
solid foundations and stability," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
