<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Trade Union for Private Sector in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's first trade union
organization for the private sector was set up recently in Lucheng
District of Wenzhou City in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The district has 1,600 privately owned small businesses with a
total employment register of 3,000 people. The union now has a
membership of 200 and its president is a waitress in a local
private teahouse.
</P>
<P>
The organization, founded at the suggestion of Nan Feiyu, vice-
president of the Self-Employed Laborers' Association in Lucheng
District of Wenzhou City, is aimed at protecting the legal rights
of employees in the private sector in line with state laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Nan first muted the idea last October when he attended the 13th
national congress of the All-China Federation of Trade Unions held
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions are allowed to be formed in government offices,
enterprises and institutions in accordance with relevant laws and
regulations. However, there are no specific guidelines on the
formation of trade unions in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Nan's idea got the support of the All-China Federation of Trade
Unions' leaders. Thus, the Zhejiang provincial trade unions
decided to take the initiative to set up such an organization in
Wenzhou on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The city is well-known for its rapid development of the private
economy in China. It has 205,000 privately owned small businesses
with an employment of 340,000 people. Registered capital totaled 2.
5 billion yuan and the private economy achieved 860 million yuan
in taxes in 1998, accounting for 19 percent of the city's total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
