<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Oil Basket Price Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's crudes basket price
closed the week Friday at 9.91 dollars per barrel, 1.06 dollars
above that of last week, the Energy and Mines Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The rising trend in oil prices, which started on March 2, is
seen as a favorable reaction to the cold wave hitting the United
States, which has resulted in a bigger volume of purchases, mainly
of fuels for heating.
</P>
<P>
The Energy and Mines weekly statistics bulletin said that
another factor that contributed to the price strengthening was the
positive outlook created around the meeting held by important
producers out or within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Major oil producers, including all OPEC members except Iraq,
are committed to cutting production from April 1 by more than two
million barrels per day (bpd), as non-OPEC members Mexico and Oman
did.
</P>
<P>
The cutbacks will be on top of existing OPEC and non-OPEC cuts
of 3.1 million bpd as agreed upon last June, exceeding five
million bpd in total.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures showed that the Venezuelan crude average
price for this year was 8.80 dollars and that of March is 9.38
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan crudes basket price dropped by 5.69 dollars per
barrel, causing a loss of 43.5 percent, equivalent to six billion
dollars in government revenue.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan crudes average price for 1998 was 10.63 dollars,
while that for 1997 was 16.32 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
