<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIS Cancels World Cup Night Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The skiing's world governing body
FIS cancelled the World Cup final slalom in the night in Sierra
Nevada on Friday as women racers threatened to go on strike due to
soft snow and icy conditions.
</P>
<P>
FIS did not reschedule the event, saying there was no time left
in the season, which ends Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Sabine Egger of Austria who entered as the overall point
leader in slalom, picks up her first World Cup season slalom title.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, fellow Austrian Alexandra Meissnitzer
claimed the season super-G title when similar weather wiped out
that race.
</P>
<P>
The first leg of the doomed slalom was run amid gusting winds
and blowing snow, with large pot holes on the course, and angry
racers protested about the conditions.
</P>
<P>
Pernilla Wiberg, one of four racers with a chance to win the
overall slalom title, said racers had agreed not to run the second
leg and were organizing to demand better conditions from FIS.
</P>
<P>
FIS called off the race as rumors circled in this southern
Spanish ski resort that the women were going on strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
