<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic Friday
formally joined NATO at a ceremony held in the city of
Independence, Missouri.
</P>
<P>
At the Harry Truman Library in Independence, the three foreign
ministers of Bronislaw Geremek of Poland, Janos Martonyi of
Hungary and Jan Kavan of the Czech Republic signed formal
documents of accession. (US-NATO-Enlargement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada Announced Friday that it scored victory at the
World Trade Organization (WTO) in a long-standing trade dispute
with Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has ruled in Canada's favor on eight o ten points, and
has declared that PROEX, a Brazilian export program, is a
prohibited export subsidy that must be withdrawn without delay,
according to a release issued by the Department of Foreign Affairs
and International Trade. (Canada-Brazil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Cambodia on Friday rejected calls for an
international trial of former Khmer Rouge leaders, insisting they
be tried in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's Foreign Minister made the statement
after meeting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hong said "The crimes committed by the
Khmer Rouge were committed in Cambodia, the culprits were
Cambodians and the victims were Cambodians." (Cambodia-Khmer
Rouge-UN)
</P>
