<HEADLINE> First Eastern Han Tile Found in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province recently discovered the first 1,800-year-old tile
ever found in the province.
</P>
<P>
The tile is said to have been produced in the Eastern Han
Dynasty (25-220 A.D.), and is carved with decorative patterns and
the two Chinese characters "Cheng Shan."
</P>
<P>
This discovery is thought to be a significant relic for the
study of the ruins of the Chengshan Palace in Meixian County, said
one Chinese archeologist.
</P>
<P>
Three Chengshan tiles made in the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C-
24 A.D.) were discovered previously, one in Meixian County in
Shaanxi in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
