<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Hails Menuhin's Unique Musical Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
paid tribute to violinist Yehudi Menuhin, who has died in Berlin
of heart failure at the age of 82.
</P>
<P>
Blair said Lord Menuhin's unique talent had brought joy to
millions and he would be "remembered the world over as one of the
greatest musicians of his age."
</P>
<P>
Lord Menuhin died in a Berlin hospital on Friday morning, after
arriving in the city on Tuesday for a concert that night.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German President Roman Herzog and French President
Jacques Chirac also called Yehudi Menuhin one of the most
brilliant musicians of the century.
</P>
<P>
Menuhin was a renowned interpreter of classical and modern
music, and also famous for establishing the Yehudi Menuhin School
in Surrey, which trained other stars.
</P>
<P>
Lord Menuhin was born in New York of Russian immigrant parents,
but became a naturalized Briton in 1985 and was knighted two years
later.
</P>
<P>
He gave up public performances in his 70s, when his hearing
become impaired, but continued conducting at his school at least
once a month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
