<HEADLINE> Clinton to Urge IRA to Disarm, Times Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
expected to urge the Irish Republican Army and its political wing
Sinn Fein to give up arms, Saturday's edition of the Times
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an authoritative source as saying that
Clinton will next week tell Adams: "It's not viable for you to say
'it can't happen, it won't happen, it's not going to happen'."
</P>
<P>
Adams and Northern Ireland's First Minister, David Trimble,
will meet Clinton next week in Washington for St. Patrick's Day
celebrations and to try to break the deadlock on IRA disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The row on decommissioning in Northern Ireland has delayed the
transfer of powers from Westminster to the provincial assembly
from March 10 to 29 and stalled the fragile peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Times said Clinton will not demand a start to
decommissioning before Sinn Fein takes its seats on the new
executive but will say that the IRA should make clear that
disarmament can and will take place.
</P>
<P>
At the same time Clinton will urge Trimble to react positively
to any such statement from the IRA and meet them half way, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton played a crucial part in persuading Protestant
unionists and Catholic republicans to sign up to the Northern
Ireland peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scottish Nationalists Launch Campaign to Win May Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Scotland's pro-independence
nationalist party launched its campaign on Friday seeking the
victory of the first general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
At the party congress, Scottish National Party (SNP) promised
victory over their ruling Labor party rivals in the vote for
Scotland's first parliament since it was last an independent
nation some 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to win... to succeed in winning equality and
independence for our country -- to be a nation again," SNP leader
Alex Salmond said in Scotland's east coastal city of Aberdeen,
according to Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
Salmond promised to hold a referendum on independence if the
SNP won control of the parliament, which will have limited tax
raising powers and be much less powerful than its Westminster
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Polls show the SNP running slightly behind British Prime
Minister Tony Blair's Labor party. Both are far ahead of the
largest opposition party the Conservative.
</P>
<P>
SNP leaders took the biggest gamble of the campaign so far by
pledging to fight government plans to cut the basic rate of income
tax by one pence in the pound -- promising to use the 690 million
pounds (1.13 billion U.S. dollars) for health and education
instead.
</P>
<P>
The tax cut, taking the basic rate to 22 percent, was the
centrepiece of finance minister Gordon Brown's budget this week, a
move the SNP labelled an attempt to "bribe" Scottish voters.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government has grown increasingly concerned about the
May vote and Blair has visited Scotland frequently in the past few
months to warn against the independent tendency in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
