<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Fails To Reach 10,000 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average moved down Friday in failure to reach 10,000 points
after the index hit 9,935.46 in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed at 9,876.35, down 21.09. The index had come
within 42 points of 10,000 in early session before pulling back.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip stock index held back from the five-digit
milestone mainly because investors decided to take profits on
the previous market surging despite more evidence that the U.S.
economy will continue to grow without inflationary threats.
</P>
<P>
The labor Department reported that the Producer Price Index
fell 0.4 percent in February after a 0.5 percent rise in
January, giving evidence that there is no inflation in
the economy.
</P>
<P>
The disappointing results for a number of companies helped
bring the index lower. Construction equipment maker Caterpillar
said its first-quarter results would fall far short of
expectations because of lower machine and engine sales.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The technology
heavy Nasdaq index was down 30.72 at 2,381.53 while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index down 3.09 at 1,294.59.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 0.13 at 611.54 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 0.44 at 721.21. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies was down 2.70 at 398.38.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,562 down, 1,406 up and 600
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 821.45 million shares from 902.62
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
