<HEADLINE> UN Announces Plan of Returning Relief Staff to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Following positive
outcomes of security assessments, the Unted Nations on Friday
announced the plan of return its international relief staff to
Afghanistan on a 2-3 week rotational basis.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, five international staff will be sent
back on March 15-21, including the Regional Security Officer, and
one representative from the World Food Program (WFP), the United
Children's Fund (UNICEF) the World Health Organization (WHO). The
Special Rapporteur on Human Rights, Mr. Kamal Hossain, will also
briefly visit Kabul in this period.
</P>
<P>
From March 22-28, a UN presence will be resumed in Khandahar
with deployment of a Field Security Officer and up to 8
international staff.
</P>
<P>
For the third week, a UN represence will remain in Kabul and
Khandahar. The subsequent opening of UN offices in Herat and
Jalalabad is also planned, and is dependent on the deployment of
Field Security Officers to those locations. Security arrangements
are expected to be finalised in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations said the further deployment of UN
international personnel and the resumption of other activities
will depend largely on how the security status within Afghanistan
unfolds in the coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
