<HEADLINE> New Car Registrations Slows Down in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The new car registrations in
Britain recorded a substantial year-by-year decrease, the
Association of European Automobile Constructors said here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the association said in a press release, the introduction
in 1999 of a twice yearly plate system, in March and September instead
of the traditional once a year system in August, has already started to
alter the established seasonality of new car registrations in Britain.
As a result, the total Western European new car market slowed down.
</P>
<P>
The association also said the Western Europe's new passenger car
registrations in February this year totalled 1,101,548 units, which
represents a decrease of 3.7 percent relative to February last year.
While the cumulative figure for the first two months of 1999 shows a
decrease of 1.7 percent compared with the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the year-over-year February evolution was particularly
good in France, Greece, Ireland, Netherlands, Portugal, Spain, and
Sweden. At the same time, Italy showed a slight decrease of 0.4
percent compared to February 1998 but taking the cumulative figure,
the decrease is nevertheless significant.
</P>
<P>
Even though Germany shows a decrease of 3.7 percent in February,
the January-February period registered a slight growth of 0.2 percent,
the car manufacturer alliance said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
