<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Rejects International Trial of Khmer Rouge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's Foreign Minister made the statement
after meeting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Hong said "The crimes committed by the
Khmer Rouge were committed in Cambodia, the culprits were
Cambodians and the victims were Cambodians."
</P>
<P>
Hong said it is logical to try the former Khmer Rouge
leaders in Cambodia because the country's constitution forbids
the extradition of its nationals to face justice in another country.
</P>
<P>
"We have to set up a national tribunal to try the Khmer Rouge
leaders. To respond to the international standards, we will
request assistance from foreign experts to the Cambodia court,"
Hong said.
</P>
<P>
Hong said his government's decision fits the provisions in
the Convention on the Repression and Punishment of the Crime of
Genocide as well as those of the Cambodian constitution.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard, Annan had insisted
the suspected criminals be tried by an international court
because "the Cambodia judiciary in its current state is unlikely
to meet the minimum standards of justice."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Annan also insisted on the need for
accountability and an end to impunity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
