<HEADLINE> German Shares Rise, Other Markets Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON March 12 (Xinhua) - The German bourse was the only
market Friday to maintain rally following the sudden resignation
of German Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine.
</P>
<P>
But other European markets fell back, depressed by Wall
Street's failure to hold on to its gains in midday trading and
break through the 10000 barrier.
</P>
<P>
German shares have soared amid hopes that Lafontaine's surprise
resignation will give a new direction to German policy.
</P>
<P>
The electronically traded Xetra Dax closed the day 245.7 points
higher at 5031.06, a jump of just over 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This surge wiped out all the losses of the previous four
session, leaving the index up 3.9 percent on the week.
</P>
<P>
Among the biggest winners were insurers, as they are likely to
benefit from the change of policy as well.
</P>
<P>
Uk shares struggled to build on Thursday's gains as profit
takers moved in on the oil sector.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 lost 53.5 points to close at 6282 after shedding
most of its modest morning gains, compared with a gain of 5.1
percent in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
French stocks opened higher after the rally on the New York and
Frankfurt stock markets as France's three largest quoted banks
square up in a take over battle, but soon fell back to end the day
little changed.
</P>
<P>
The leading Cac 40 index was down 9 points to close at 4175.
</P>
</TEXT>
