<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Hold Consultations on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the United States
agreed here Friday on the necessity of a peaceful solution to the
Afghanistan conflict.
</P>
<P>
During a five-hour session of consultations between Russian
Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory Karasin and U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State Carl Inderfurth, the two sides stressed the
importance of U.N.-led international assistance in attracting all
Afghan religious, ethnic and political movements to the peace
process, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Moscow and Washington are positive that "the long-term
settlement in Afghanistan is possible only on such a broad basis,"
Interfax quoted Karasin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Karasin said the two sides also discussed practical measures in
fighting terrorism and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Both countries urge the Taliban movement and its supporters to
ensure that international terrorist Usma bin Laden be expelled
from Afghanistan and brought to trial, Inderfurth said.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, participants in the
inter-Afghan talks in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan, pledged to continue
negotiations until agreements are reached, acting chief of the
U.N. mission in Afghanistan Andrew Tesoriere said Friday. 
</P>
