<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Armenian Minister of Industry and
Trade Gaik Gevorkyan on Friday hailed the signing of a trade
agreement as a turning point in his country's trade relations with
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Gevorkyan expressed his appreciation of the accord after he
signed it with Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili.
</P>
<P>
He said the pact will afford "a big opportunity" to lay the
groundwork for promoting the bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
He urged Egyptian commercial banks to open branches or set up
joint banks in his country to finance the trade exchange.
</P>
<P>
The Armenian official called on Egyptian businessmen to visit
Armenia to get to know the local market and acquaint Armenian
consumers with Egyptian products, which he said have high quality
and competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili said that opportunities are existing for Egyptian
engineering, farming and consumer goods in Armenia, where these
products are in great demand.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is aimed at enhancing the bilateral trade volume,
which lags at 4 million U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Gevorkyan arrived here on Monday leading a business delegation
to the 32nd Cairo International Fair running on March 9-19.
