<HEADLINE> NATO Formally Adds New Members From Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) becomes a 19-ally military power as the Czech
Republic, Poland and Hungary formally joined the 16-member bloc
Friday, the day NATO said opens a new chapter in the history of
the Atlantic Alliance and of Europe.
</P>
<P>
NATO's decision-making body, the North Atlantic Council, said
in a statement that it welcomes the three new Eastern European
allies who formally accede to the Washington Treaty which shaped
the organization after World War Two.
</P>
<P>
The council said that next Tuesday NATO will receive the prime
ministers of the three new members here in Brussels. "Their flags
will be raised alongside those of the other 16 member countries at
a ceremony of welcome. They will then take their seats at the
table of the North Atlantic Council as full and equal allies," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO supremacy body also said that the alliance's opening
process to new countries is part of NATO's policy to improve the
security and stability environment for nations in the
Euro-Atlantic area. "The countries of Europe are moving closer
together to finally overcome the division of Europe."
</P>
<P>
At its 50th anniversary celebrations in Washington next month,
NATO will proclaim a so-called "new strategy concept" on orienting
its future direction for the alliance of 19 members: Belgium,
Iceland, Denmark, Germany, France, the Netherlands, Canada,
Luxembourg, the United States, Norway, Portugal, Turkey, Spain,
Greece, Italy, Britain, Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
