<HEADLINE> Three Americans to Appear in Zimbabwean Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Three Americans arrested on Sunday
at the Harare International Airport with a huge assortment of
arms of war will appear in court on Saturday morning, Police said
on Friday in Zimbabwean capital.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri told reporters
that the Americans would be charged under a section of the Law
and Order Maintenance Act which deals with acts of terrorism and
sabotage.
</P>
<P>
Chihuri said police investigations had discovered that the
Americans rented a house in Harare and another in the town of
Lubumbashi in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) where arms
of war were also recovered.
</P>
<P>
He said the Americans were on a mission of acts of terrorism,
sabotage and to destabilize both Zimbabwe and the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"They were on spying missions for rebels in the DRC and the
three had contacts in Zimbabwe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chihuri, who was flanked by Director-General of the Central
Intelligence Organization Elisha Muzonzini and Acting Information
Director Edward Mamutse, said the excuse by the Americans that
they were hunters was just a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
He said investigations had shown that the Americans had never
been to any hunting game park in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The police chief declined to name the Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Americans were arrested on Sunday following the discovery
of the arms of war which included AK-47 riffles, pistols,
shotguns, ammunition, binoculars and communication equipment as
they prepared to board a Swiss airplane to Zurich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
