<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Official Appeals for Legal Rights of The </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan social welfare official
said here Friday that the country should pass a law to guarantee
the rights of the handicapped, most of whom became disabled in
wars against colonialism or civil wars during the past three
decades.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Angolan National Association for the
Handicapped, Silva Lopes Etiambulo, said that enactment of laws
for the handicapped would help maintain social stability as the
country is having more and more beggars and armed robberies.
</P>
<P>
Etiambulo said that the country should first pass an act for
the handicapped to ensure their basic rights of living, education
and work, then give favorable treatment to them in medicare,
transportation, food, housing and bank loans.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government has made great efforts in helping
the handicapped, such as establishing a health recovery center and
working out programs for their education and employment. However,
he said the government's efforts to assist the handicapped have
faced financial constrains as the civil war continues.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics of the association show that the
handicapped persons in Angola are currently estimated at 800,000,
some eight percent of the country's total population. Around
150,000 people were handicapped by land mines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
