<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister Denies Wrongdoing in Obtaining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of State for
Education Francis Babu has denied any wrongdoing in obtaining a
certificate required for application for Master of Business
Administration (MBA).
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Friday evening, the minister said the
academic qualifications he submitted to Makerere University are an
equivalent to a first degree as verified by the Aviation Training
Association in Britain.
</P>
<P>
But he accepted the decision by the university to cancel his
admission to the post-graduate of MBA.
</P>
<P>
He was duly admitted because there were no discrepancies in his
academic qualifications but only to be dismissed six moths later,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In a letter dated March 10 to the minister, the Academic
Registrar of the university, Hyuha Mulwanason, said the minister
had been discontinued because he did not have a first degree of
its equivalent which is the minimum requirement under the
university's rule to enrol for a MBA degree.
</P>
<P>
Some official in the university, who preferred anonymity, was
quoted by the New Vision daily as saying recently that the
minister was not admitted through the board responsible for
postgraduate studies, but through influence peddling, a charge
the minister denied. 
</P>
</TEXT>
