<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Not to Allow Foreign Troops into Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic reiterated on Friday that his country will not allow
foreign troops to be stationed in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The president of the federal republic made this remark while
meeting Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov who forwarded a
letter written by Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic told the visiting foreign minister that the
continuation of the peace talks in Paris starting next Monday
should only conclude by reaching a political agreement, ruling out
any military means in the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
He promised that both Serbia and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia are determined to guarantee autonomy for Kosovo within
Serbia on the basis of full equality of all nationalities and in
accordance with the highest norms of international law.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav president told the visitor that Yugoslavia would
send its delegation to Paris for the second round of peace talks
and would contribute their efforts toward reaching a political
agreement aimed at guaranteeing equal social status and rights for
all residents in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister said at the meeting that his
country has been championing a political solution through peaceful
means and that Russia expects a political solution could be found
on the foundation of the peace plan formulated by the six-nation
Contact Group that consists of the United States, Britain, France,
Germany, Italy and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov stressed that Russia is opposed to either the threat of
force and the use of force against the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and that as a member of the Contact Group, Russia has
been against the stationing of foreign troops in the Yugoslav
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
