<HEADLINE> Uganda Releases Fund for Dam Building in Nomadic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
released 3.3 billion shillings (about 3.3 million U.S. dollars)
=
nw=9struction of dams in Karamoja, a nomadic region in
northeastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The funds were remitted to the Ministry of Water, Lands and
Environment and plans to start the construction of dams are under
way, Radio Uganda reported Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Minister Akika Othieno was quoted as saying that the priority
is to provide water for livestock in the region. He noted that
the Karamoja region lacks water for people and charged the
district leaders to ensure proper management and maintenance of
existing bore-holes.
</P>
<P>
The constructors of the dams should be monitored and supervised
by district authorities to ensure proper accountability and
adequate work, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Karamoja has been neglected by all successive
post-independence governments. It is semi-arid and characterized
by lack of water supply, food shortage and poor communication.
</P>
<P>
The people there are nomads moving around in search of pasture
and water for their animals. Cattle rustling and insecurity have
been the common features of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
