<HEADLINE> U.S., British Warplanes Again Bomb Iraqi Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes
bombed some Iraqi military sites and civilian installations in
northern Iraq on Friday, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The damages and casualties of the attack were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the spokesman as saying that
around noon Friday, nine formations of U.S. and British warplanes
including F-15 and F-16 fighters taking off from Turkey violated
northern Iraqi airspace over Erbil, Dohuk and Neineva provinces.
</P>
<P>
The warplanes fired seven missiles and bombs at some civilian
facilities and anti-aircraft positions, said the spokesman,
adding that Iraqi air defenses fired back and the warplanes fled
at 3:10 p.m. local time (1210 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Confrontations between Iraqi air-defenses and the U.S. and
British warplanes patrolling the two no-fly zones have almost
become a daily occurrence over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad announced it does not recognize the no-fly zones
following the four-day U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq last
December and would fire at any warplane violating its airspace.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq after
the 1991 Gulf War, with the claimed aim of protecting the Kurds in
the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's
suppression." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
