<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Expects to Keep Current Bomber Fleet for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force's bomber
fleet, which includes B-52s that have been flying since before the
Vietnam War, will have to last another 40 years, an Air Force's
official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, said 3.6 billion
U.S. dollars is being invested over the next 10 years to upgrade
the fleet -- giving it more advanced communications links and
newer precision-guided weapons.
</P>
<P>
But the Air Force does not intend to even begin planning for a
next-generation bomber until about 2013, Air Force Secretary
Whitten Peters said.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force timeline indicates that the current bomber fleet,
which totals 190 aircraft -- 93 B-1 Lancers, 76 B-52
Stratofortresses and 21 B-2 Spirits -- will be worn out by about
2037. The B-52s, which were built in 1960 and 1961, might last
until 2044, by which time they would be 84 years old.
</P>
<P>
Although the Air Force would like to bring on a new generation
of bombers earlier, it cannot afford to move faster. The main
priority in aircraft development over the next two decades will be
new fighter planes -- the F-22 stealth plane and the so-called
Joint Strike Fighter -- to replace today's F-15s and F-16s.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force estimates it spent 30 billion dollars building
the B-1 fleet and 45 billion dollars on the B-2s. The B-52 is so
old and has undergone so many changes that the Air Force has no
estimate of its total cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
