<HEADLINE> Six Local Journalists Released in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Lusaka High Court Friday
released all the six reporters of the Post newspaper and ordered
the government to compensate them for wrongful detention.
</P>
<P>
But Principal State Advocate, Donald Kasote, indicated that the
 reporters, who allegedly revealed state secrets, could be
re-arrested at a later stage as investigations could be going on.
</P>
<P>
He, however, assured the court that the reporters would not be
re- arrested immediately.
</P>
<P>
Defense Counsel, Sakiwba Sikota, expressed fears that the
reporters could be re-arrested because the state had not clearly
stated whether or not they had withdrawn a case against them.
</P>
<P>
Judge Elliot Chulu ordered that the reporters should be set
free and expressed dissatisfaction with the manner the state
detained the reporters and failed to bring them to court on
Thursday when the matter came up for hearing.
</P>
<P>
The police made the arrests following directives from the
Deputy Speaker of the National Assembly, Simon Mwila, to Defense
Minister Chitalu Sampa on Tuesday to take appropriate action
against their newspaper for its front- page story carried on
Tuesday --Angola worries Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that Zambia is in no position to withstand a
military attack from Angola, in the story there are some details
on the country's military force.  
