<HEADLINE> U.S. Navy Punishes Sailors for Rejecting Anthrax Shots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Navy said Friday that
it had punished 23 sailors bound for the Gulf who refused
compulsory anthrax shots which will protect them against the
deadly biological agent.
</P>
<P>
The group is the largest to refuse the vaccine, which U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered for all members of the
military more than a year ago. Those who refuse the vaccine
believe it has not been thoroughly tested and could damage their
health.
</P>
<P>
The 23 sailors from the USS Theodore Roosevelt aircraft carrier
were demoted by one rank, given 45 days extra duty, restricted to
the vessel for 45 days and ordered to pay fines equal to one
month's pay, said Mark McDonald, a spokesman for the U.S. Atlantic
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The USS Theodore Roosevelt, which is based in Norfolk, Virginia
State of the United States, is expected to leave on March 26 for a
six-month tour that includes time in the Gulf, a potential anthrax
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
