<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Nordic Countries Cut Aid to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Three Nordic countries have
reduced their aid to Kenya by two-thirds in the past five years,
their envoys said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors from Sweden, Finland and Norway said that the
multi-million- shilling development aid package to Kenya had been
seriously downsized.
</P>
<P>
The three envoys said that the donor community in their home
countries will meet with Kenya government officials next month to
review progress made on certain conditions before the resumption
of aid.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors did not reveal whether or not their governments
were satisfied with the progress that Kenyan government had made
on some controversial issues.
</P>
<P>
The envoys did not give the exact figures of how much aid Kenya
used to get from their countries before the decline.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Ambassador to Kenya, Inga Bjork Klevby, said his
country had sharply reduced aid to Kenya, adding that Kenya
currently receives a mere one-third of the amount five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Klevby also said that Sweden welcomed the 16-year plan to
eliminate poverty unveiled by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian Ambassador Per Haugestad claimed that some of the
economic issues in Kenya could be tackled by the Kenyan government
in co-operation with donors and friendly countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990313.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 500,000 People in Central Kenya Need Famine Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- About half a million people in
Kenya's Central Province require famine relief during the current
drought period, according to a report from the Ministry of
Agriculture available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 13 percent of the province's population
needs 332, 494 bags (90 kg per bag) of maize and 117,100 bags of
beans.
</P>
<P>
The provincial crops official E.G. Waithaka said in the
February Crop and Food Situation Report that the only maize
available in the local market is from Rift Valley and Western
provinces. Other food selling at the market are only bananas and
sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that even in the best of seasons, the province
produces 49 percent of its maize needed by the province's
population with the rest imported from other provinces.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that Kirinyaga District tops the list of
areas in urgent need of relief supplies with Maragwa District
ranking the second.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the failure of the short rains between October and
November last year, most of the crops in the province had become
severely water- stressed, the report said, adding that maize from
the highland areas was harvested green.
</P>
<P>
Beans, Irish potatoes, bananas and cotton were also affected.
For this reason, the yields slumped to 0.2 bags per hectare for
beans and 25 bags per hectare for Irish potatoes.
</P>
<P>
The repof4Efurther noted that the last two months had been very
hot and dry with an average of only four or three wet days in
those districts in January.
</P>
<P>
The official said to enable farmers in Central Province recover
from the effects of drought, 493 tons of maize seeds and 668 tons
of bean seeds are urgently needed in the long rains period
beginning this month.
</P>
<P>
Kajiado District agricultural official Geoffrey Kituyi reported
in mid- February that the majority of farmers in his district had
no food reserves and seeds for planting during the long rains,
because the grain stored earlier was destroyed by the larger
grain borer due to the poor pesticides used.  
</P>
</TEXT>
